question:
I am a 7-year-old boy, and my mother brought me to the physician to discuss some issues I've been experiencing. For the past six months, I have had abdominal pain, particularly crampy sensations every morning on school days. I started at a new school seven months ago, and my mother is worried because I've missed school frequently due to this pain.

In addition to the abdominal discomfort, I have been having trouble falling asleep at night. I often ask to sleep in the same room as my parents, which seems to help me feel more secure. I have not experienced any fever, vomiting, diarrhea, or weight loss during this time.

When we were at the doctor's office, I found myself sitting very close to my mother and felt upset when she stepped out of the room to take a phone call. The doctor examined my abdomen and found no abnormalities. My mother and I are both curious about what might be causing these symptoms.
options: A. Separation anxiety disorder B. Normal behavior C. Irritable bowel syndrome D. Conduct disorder E. Acute stress disorder
default: It sounds like you might be experiencing anxiety, especially since your symptoms started after changing schools and you've been feeling upset when separated from your mother. The abdominal pain and trouble sleeping can often be linked to stress or anxiety in children. It's important to talk to your doctor about these feelings, as they can help find ways to manage your anxiety and make you feel more comfortable. Your mother can also support you by helping you feel secure and discussing any worries you might have about school or other changes.

question:
I am a 23-year-old woman who was brought to the emergency department by my boyfriend due to a persistent feeling of sadness that has lasted for four months. During this time, I have been sleeping and eating very little, and I have struggled to focus at work. I often feel empty inside and have begun hearing voices that tell me I am worthless. The first time I heard these voices was seven months ago, and they made fun of me.

I do not consume alcohol or use any illicit drugs. When I was examined, both physical and neurological assessments showed no abnormalities. However, during the mental status examination, my speech was noted to be slow and monotonous. At times, I abruptly stop talking mid-sentence and do not finish my thoughts. I also find myself occasionally looking up at the ceiling as if I am listening to someone. This experience has been distressing for me and has significantly impacted my daily life.
options: A. Schizophrenia B. Schizophreniform disorder C. Brief psychotic disorder D. Schizoaffective disorder E. Mood disorder with psychotic features F. Schizotypal personality disorder
default: Based on the symptoms described, it appears you may be experiencing a major depressive episode with psychotic features, particularly given the persistent sadness, changes in sleep and appetite, difficulty concentrating, feelings of worthlessness, and auditory hallucinations. The slow and monotonous speech, along with the abrupt pauses and looking up as if listening, further suggest a significant impact on your cognitive and emotional functioning. It is crucial to seek a comprehensive psychiatric evaluation to confirm the diagnosis and discuss appropriate treatment options, which may include therapy and medication.

question:
I am a 37-year-old man who recently went to the emergency department with my wife due to severe pain in my right arm that has lasted for three days. This pain began one morning after I woke up, having slept on my side, and since then, I have been unable to move my right arm. I generally consider myself healthy, but I have been feeling increasingly exhausted from working several night shifts each week as a waiter. 

During the day, I struggle to stay awake, especially while caring for our daughter, and I often feel like I can barely keep my eyes open. Because of the pain, I have been unable to work, which has placed additional financial strain on my family. My wife has taken on an extra shift to help cover our monthly bills.

When I arrived at the emergency department, I felt relaxed but hesitant to allow the medical team to examine me until my wife encouraged me to cooperate. The medical staff noted that my vital signs were within normal limits. Upon examination, I had very limited muscle strength in my right arm and no sensation to light touch over the entire area. However, when a pin prick test was performed, I reflexively withdrew my right arm.
options: A. Brachial neuritis B. Factitious disorder C. Somatic symptom disorder D. Malingering E. Conversion disorder F. Radial nerve palsy G. Illness anxiety disorder
default:
Based on your symptoms and the examination findings, it seems you may be experiencing a condition known as "shoulder-hand syndrome" or possibly a cervical radiculopathy, which can occur due to nerve compression or injury, often related to sleeping positions or repetitive strain. The severe pain, limited movement, and sensory changes suggest a neurological component, possibly involving the brachial plexus or cervical spine.

The fact that you can withdraw your arm to a pin prick indicates that there is some preserved reflex activity, which is a positive sign. However, the lack of sensation to light touch and significant muscle weakness are concerning and warrant further investigation, such as imaging studies (like an MRI) to assess for any structural issues.

question:
I was involved in a motor vehicle accident and was brought to the emergency department. Upon arrival, I was unconscious and had been intubated in the field. My medical history was unknown to the medical staff. I presented with hypotension and tachycardia. 

My vital signs indicated a temperature of 37.2°C (99.1°F), a pulse rate of 110 beats per minute, and a respiratory rate of 22 breaths per minute. My blood pressure was recorded at 85/60 mm Hg. Medical personnel noted no signs of head trauma; I was responsive to pain stimuli, and my pupils measured 2mm and reacted to light. 

The examination of my heart revealed a regular rhythm without murmurs or rubs, and my lungs were clear upon auscultation. However, my abdomen was firm and distended, and bowel sounds were decreased. My extremities felt cool and clammy, with weak, thready pulses, but there was no peripheral edema. 

Given these findings, the medical team would need to determine the likely cause of my condition.
options: A. Neurogenic shock B. Cardiogenic shock C. Obstructive shock D. Hypovolemic shock E. Septic shock
default: Based on the provided information, the most likely cause of your condition is hypovolemic shock due to internal bleeding, possibly from abdominal trauma. The firm and distended abdomen, decreased bowel sounds, hypotension, tachycardia, and cool, clammy extremities suggest significant blood loss and inadequate perfusion. Immediate imaging and surgical evaluation would be necessary to identify and address the source of the bleeding.

question:
I am a 24-year-old woman who arrived at the emergency department with my boyfriend about two hours after I lost consciousness. I was seated getting a tattoo on my right upper flank when I suddenly became sweaty and pale before passing out. My boyfriend told me that I slipped to the floor and my arms and legs moved in a jerky manner for a few seconds. Fortunately, I regained consciousness within half a minute and felt alert and fully oriented right after.

I do not have a history of serious illness. I work as an event manager, and I have been experiencing more stress than usual lately due to a recent concert tour. When examined in the emergency department, I appeared well. My vital signs were stable; my temperature was 37°C, my pulse was 68 beats per minute, my respirations were 16 per minute, and my blood pressure was 120/72 mm Hg. 

The examination of my cardiopulmonary system showed no abnormalities, and the neurologic exam revealed no focal findings. An ECG indicated an incomplete right bundle branch block. I am now waiting for further evaluation to understand what might have caused my episode.
options:
A. Carotid sinus hypersensitivity B. Vasovagal syncope C. Orthostatic syncope D. Panic attack E. Tonic-clonic seizure F. Cardiac arrhythmia G. Cardiac structural abnormality
"
default: Based on your description, it sounds like you experienced a syncopal episode, possibly related to vasovagal syncope, especially given the context of stress and the setting of getting a tattoo. The jerky movements you described could indicate a brief postictal state, but the rapid recovery and full orientation suggest it was not a seizure. The incomplete right bundle branch block on your ECG is often benign, especially in young individuals. Further evaluation may include monitoring for arrhythmias, blood tests, and possibly an echocardiogram to rule out any underlying cardiac issues. Stress management techniques may also be beneficial moving forward.

question:
I am a 55-year-old man who recently attended a routine check-up. During this visit, I had no complaints and my previous physical and laboratory tests had been unremarkable. My medical history includes hypercholesterolemia, which is well managed with rosuvastatin, and hypertension, which I manage with hydrochlorothiazide. Additionally, I take aspirin as part of my medication regimen.

At the appointment, I was afebrile and my vital signs were within normal limits. However, during the physical examination, my doctor noted some generalized lymphadenopathy. Following this, a blood test was conducted. The results showed an elevated white blood cell count, a normal red blood cell count, and a low hematocrit and hemoglobin level. The platelet count was within the normal range. A peripheral blood smear revealed that 92% of my cells were small normocytic lymphocytes.

Given these findings, my doctor further assessed my condition to determine the most likely diagnosis. While I am currently unaware of the specific diagnosis, I understand that my symptoms and test results are being carefully evaluated.
options: A. Acute myelogenous leukemia B. Acute lymphocytic leukemia C. Chronic myelogenous leukemia D. Chronic lymphocytic leukemia E. Asymptomatic multiple myeloma
default: Based on your symptoms and test results, the most likely diagnosis is chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL). The presence of generalized lymphadenopathy, elevated white blood cell count with a predominance of small normocytic lymphocytes, and normal red blood cell and platelet counts are characteristic of this condition. It’s important to follow up with your healthcare provider for further evaluation and management.

question:
I underwent a lung transplant due to idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis. Unfortunately, I later experienced hypercapnic respiratory failure, which ultimately led to my passing. Following my death, an investigator performed an autopsy to study the effects of immune-mediated pulmonary damage. 

During the autopsy, the investigator examined my lungs and noted diffuse eosinophilic scarring in the terminal and respiratory bronchioles. There was also nearly complete luminal obstruction caused by polypoidal plugs of granulation tissue. Additionally, the investigator checked my skin and found no abnormalities. 

These findings were significant in understanding the condition I had experienced leading up to my death. The insights gained from this examination may contribute to further research in similar cases involving lung transplants and immune-related pulmonary issues.
options: A. Transfusion-related acute lung injury B. Recurrence of primary disease C. Hyperacute graft rejection D. Chronic graft rejection E. Acute graft-versus-host disease F. Acute graft rejection
default: The autopsy findings suggest that you experienced significant post-transplant complications, likely related to chronic rejection or an immune-mediated process affecting the lungs. The diffuse eosinophilic scarring and luminal obstruction by granulation tissue indicate a form of airway remodeling, possibly linked to conditions like bronchiolitis obliterans syndrome (BOS), which is a common complication after lung transplantation. The absence of skin abnormalities suggests that the immune response was primarily localized to the lungs rather than systemic. These insights are crucial for understanding the mechanisms of transplant rejection and may guide future therapeutic strategies to mitigate similar complications in lung transplant recipients.

question:
I was admitted to the emergency room after experiencing intense abdominal pain for about eight hours. The pain was severe and radiated to my back. I also felt nauseous and had multiple episodes of vomiting. My medical history had no significant issues prior to this incident.

Upon arrival, the medical team noted that my blood pressure was quite low at 90/60 mm Hg, and my pulse was elevated at 120 beats per minute. My respiratory rate was 20 breaths per minute, and I had a slight fever with a temperature of 37.8°C (100°F). During the examination, the doctors found significant tenderness in my epigastric area and noted that my bowel sounds were hypoactive.

As my condition deteriorated, it became necessary to transfer me to the intensive care unit for a month. After being stabilized, I was moved to the general medicine floor. A CT scan of my abdomen revealed a well-circumscribed collection of fluid with a homogeneous density. This sequence of events has left me with a clearer understanding of my condition.
options: A. Pancreatic pseudocyst B. Walled-off necrosis C. Acute necrotic collection D. Pancreatic cancer E. Fistula formation
default: Based on your symptoms and the findings from the CT scan, it appears you may have experienced an acute abdominal condition, possibly pancreatitis or an abdominal abscess. The severe abdominal pain radiating to your back, low blood pressure, elevated heart rate, and hypoactive bowel sounds suggest a significant underlying issue, likely involving inflammation or infection. The well-circumscribed fluid collection seen on the CT scan could indicate a fluid collection related to pancreatitis or an abscess. Close monitoring and treatment in the ICU were necessary due to your deteriorating condition, but stabilization and transfer to the general medicine floor indicate improvement. Further management will depend on the specific diagnosis and the nature of the fluid collection.

question:
I am a 36-year-old man who recently experienced massive hematemesis. My medical history includes a gastric ulcer. When I arrived for treatment, my pulse was 115 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 20 breaths per minute, and my temperature was measured at 36°C (96.8°F). My blood pressure was low at 90/59 mm Hg.

During my treatment, I received a transfusion of 2 units of packed red blood cells. Shortly after the transfusion began, specifically around 5 to 10 minutes later, I started to feel chills and experienced pain in my lower back. I also noticed a decrease in my urine output. My vital signs changed; my pulse increased to 118 beats per minute, my respiratory rate decreased slightly to 19 breaths per minute, and my temperature rose to 38°C (100.4°F). My blood pressure dropped further to 60/40 mm Hg.

These symptoms prompted further evaluation to determine the underlying cause of my condition.
options: A. Acute hemolytic transfusion reaction B. Anaphylactic transfusion reaction C. Febrile non-hemolytic transfusion reaction D. Transfusion-associated sepsis E. Transfusion-related acute lung injury
default:
Based on the symptoms and timeline you provided, it appears you may be experiencing an acute transfusion reaction, likely a hemolytic transfusion reaction. The chills, back pain, fever, and significant drop in blood pressure shortly after the transfusion began are classic signs of this type of reaction. The decrease in urine output could indicate acute kidney injury, possibly due to hemolysis.

Immediate evaluation and management are crucial. This includes stopping the transfusion, maintaining venous access with normal saline, and notifying the medical team. Further tests, such as a complete blood count, blood cultures, and possibly a direct Coombs test, should be performed to confirm the diagnosis and assess for hemolysis.

question:
I am a 52-year-old woman, and for the past six months, I have been experiencing intermittent diffuse abdominal pain that intensifies after I eat. Along with this pain, I have had several episodes of diarrhea, the most recent of which was bloody. These symptoms began to appear gradually but have worsened recently. As a result of these ongoing issues, I have noticed significant weight loss.

Additionally, I have a medical history of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), which has been challenging to manage. During my recent check-up, my vital signs were recorded, showing a blood pressure of 100/70 mm Hg, a temperature of 37.1°C (98.8 °F), and a pulse rate of 95 beats per minute. During the physical examination, I appeared to be in severe pain, and the doctor noted mild diffuse abdominal tenderness.

Given the combination of my symptoms and medical history, I am seeking clarification on the most likely diagnosis for my condition.
options: A. Gastroenteritis B. Ischemic bowel disease C. Ulcerative colitis D. Small bowel obstruction E. Acute pancreatitis
default: Based on your symptoms—intermittent diffuse abdominal pain that worsens after eating, episodes of diarrhea (including bloody diarrhea), significant weight loss, and your history of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)—the most likely diagnosis is mesenteric ischemia or inflammatory bowel disease (IBD), such as ulcerative colitis or Crohn's disease. The bloody diarrhea and weight loss are particularly concerning and warrant further investigation, such as imaging studies or endoscopy, to determine the exact cause and appropriate treatment. It's crucial to follow up with your healthcare provider promptly for a thorough evaluation.

question:
I am a 51-year-old woman who recently visited the emergency department due to an aggressive cough that has persisted for about 11 years. This cough often produces copious amounts of thick, foamy, yellow-green sputum. I have experienced exacerbations similar to this one over the years, and I notice that the cough tends to worsen in the morning.

Throughout this time, I have sought medical attention multiple times for recurrent bouts of bronchitis, which have required antibiotic treatment. I do not smoke. During my examination, my blood pressure was recorded at 125/78 mm Hg, my pulse rate was 80 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 16 breaths per minute, and my temperature was 36.7°C (98.0°F). 

The doctor listened to my chest and noted crackles and wheezing in the right middle lobe, while the rest of the physical examination results appeared normal. A chest X-ray was performed, revealing irregular opacities in the right middle lobe and diffuse airway thickening. These findings, combined with my medical history, have led to further discussions regarding a potential diagnosis.
options: A. Tuberculosis B. Alpha-1-antitrypsin deficiency C. Bronchiectasis D. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease E. Chronic bronchitis
default: Based on your symptoms and medical history, it is likely that you may have bronchiectasis. The persistent cough with copious thick sputum, recurrent bronchitis, and the chest X-ray findings of irregular opacities and airway thickening are characteristic of this condition. Bronchiectasis often results from chronic inflammation or infection of the airways, leading to the dilation and damage of bronchial tubes. Further evaluation, including a CT scan of the chest and possibly sputum cultures, would be important to confirm the diagnosis and assess for any underlying causes.

question:
I am a 35-year-old man who experienced shortness of breath while playing football with friends. This episode began about an hour into the game. I have had similar instances in the past that required emergency care. 

Upon arriving at the emergency room, my body temperature was recorded at 37.2°C, with a pulse rate of 100 beats per minute and a respiratory rate of 28 breaths per minute. My blood pressure was measured at 110/60 mm Hg. The examination revealed decreased breath sounds on both sides. My peak expiratory flow rate was 200 L/min, and my oxygen saturation was at 89% while breathing room air.

The medical team initiated treatment with nebulization using a short-acting β-agonist. I was also given oxygen via a mask. After oxygen administration, my oxygen levels improved, with a recorded partial pressure of oxygen increasing to 75 mm Hg. 

I am aware that my condition often leads to hospital visits, and I am seeking to understand the underlying cause of these episodes of shortness of breath.
options: A. Asthma attack B. Carbon monoxide (CO) poisoning C. Atelectasis D. Neuromuscular disease E. Acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS)
default:
Based on your symptoms and history, it sounds like you may be experiencing exercise-induced bronchoconstriction, which is common in individuals with asthma or reactive airway disease. The shortness of breath during physical activity, decreased breath sounds, low peak expiratory flow rate, and low oxygen saturation suggest that your airways may be constricting, leading to difficulty in breathing.

The fact that you have had similar episodes requiring emergency care indicates that this is a recurrent issue, likely related to an underlying respiratory condition. The treatment you received, including nebulization with a short-acting β-agonist and supplemental oxygen, is typical for managing acute asthma exacerbations.

It would be beneficial to follow up with a healthcare provider for further evaluation, including possible allergy testing

question:
I am a 70-year-old woman, and for the past two weeks, I have been experiencing severe fatigue. Over the last month, I have unintentionally lost about 2 kilograms (4.4 pounds). Three years ago, I was diagnosed with myelodysplastic syndrome. Currently, I do not take any medications aside from aspirin for occasional knee pain. I neither smoke nor drink alcohol.

During my recent visit to the doctor, my vital signs were recorded as normal. However, the examination revealed that my conjunctivae appeared pale. I also had petechiae on the distal parts of my lower extremities and on both my soft and hard palates. When my doctor palpated my neck, they noted bilateral painless cervical lymphadenopathy. An examination of my lungs, heart, and abdomen showed no abnormalities.

The doctor conducted some laboratory studies, but I do not have the results from those tests. I am aware that the findings during my examination raised some concerns, and I am waiting to understand more about what might be causing my symptoms and the changes observed during the physical examination.
options: A. Acute myeloid leukemia B. Aplastic anemia C. Chronic myelogenous leukemia D. Hairy cell leukemia E. Primary myelofibrosis
default: Given your history of myelodysplastic syndrome, the symptoms of severe fatigue, unintentional weight loss, pale conjunctivae, petechiae, and bilateral painless cervical lymphadenopathy are concerning for a possible progression of your underlying condition or the development of a secondary issue, such as acute leukemia or another hematological disorder. The pale conjunctivae suggest anemia, while the petechiae indicate potential thrombocytopenia. The lymphadenopathy could point to an underlying malignancy or infection. It's crucial to follow up with your doctor once the laboratory results are available, as they will provide more insight into your blood counts and any abnormalities that may explain your symptoms.

question:
I am an 8-year-old boy, and I was taken to the emergency department about three hours after experiencing a concerning episode at school. While I was in class, I had a two-minute incident where my right arm moved violently and jerkily. During this time, I was sweating a lot, but I did not lose consciousness. Before the episode began, I felt a chill run down my spine.

After the jerking stopped, I noticed that my right arm felt weak, and I couldn't lift it above my head for about two hours. A few weeks prior to this incident, I had a sore throat, which went away after I took some over-the-counter medicine.

I was born at term, and my mom recalls that I had a similar episode of jerky movements when I was a toddler and had a high fever. There is no significant family history of illnesses, although my father passed away in a car accident about a year ago. When examined at the hospital, my temperature was normal, my pulse was steady, and my blood pressure was measured. Both physical and neurological exams did not reveal any abnormalities. Blood tests for various levels showed everything was within the normal range.
options: A. Sydenham chorea B. Sporadic transient tic disorder C. Conversion disorder D. Hemiplegic migraine E. Focal seizure
default:
Based on the information provided, it sounds like you may have experienced a focal seizure, specifically a focal motor seizure affecting your right arm. The jerky movements, sweating, and subsequent weakness in your arm align with this type of seizure. The previous similar episode during childhood, especially with a high fever, could suggest a history of febrile seizures, which are common in young children. 

It's important to follow up with a pediatric neurologist for further evaluation, which may include an EEG or imaging studies, to better understand the cause of these episodes and to determine if any treatment is necessary.

question:
I am a 56-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department due to increasing crampy abdominal pain and swelling that had developed over the past two days. I had not passed stool or flatus for over 12 hours and experienced vomiting twice during this period. Notably, I had observed a decrease in the caliber of my stools over the past month.

My medical history is generally unremarkable, except for having undergone an appendectomy eight years ago. I do not take any medications. Upon arrival at the emergency department, my vital signs were recorded: my temperature was 37.5°C (99.5°F), my pulse was 82 beats per minute, my respirations were 19 breaths per minute, and my blood pressure was 110/70 mm Hg.

The examination of my abdomen revealed symmetric distension with active bowel sounds and generalized tenderness, but there was no guarding or rebound tenderness. A leukocyte count was also assessed, showing a count of 10,000/mm³. X-rays of my abdomen were taken in both upright and supine positions. I was informed that these findings would help determine the underlying cause of my recent condition.
options: A. Acute mesenteric ischemia B. Adhesions C. Diverticulitis D. Ogilvie’s syndrome E. Sigmoid tumor
default: Based on the symptoms and findings described, you are likely experiencing a bowel obstruction. The key indicators include the crampy abdominal pain, abdominal distension, lack of stool or flatus for over 12 hours, vomiting, and the noted decrease in stool caliber over the past month. The abdominal X-rays will help identify the presence of air-fluid levels or dilated bowel loops, which are characteristic of obstruction. Given your history of appendectomy, a possible cause could be adhesions from the previous surgery. It is important to further evaluate and manage this condition promptly to prevent complications.

question:
I was brought to the emergency department by police officers after acting strangely in public. I was found talking nonsensically to characters on cereal boxes in a store. I am 60 years old, and my medical history includes multiple hospitalizations due to alcohol-related injuries and seizures. 

Upon arrival, my vital signs were checked and found to be within normal limits. During the physical examination, I appeared disheveled and was oriented to my identity but not to the time or place. The neurologic examination revealed that I had nystagmus and severe gait ataxia. 

To assess my condition further, a T1/T2 MRI was performed, which showed evidence of damage to my mammillary bodies. I received appropriate treatment, which helped me recover most of my cognitive functions. However, I continue to experience significant short-term memory deficits. I can still recall events from my past, including the schools and college I attended, my current job, and the names of my family members quite well. Despite these improvements, I struggle with new information and recent events.
options: A. Delirium B. Delirium tremens C. Korsakoff's syndrome D. Schizophrenia E. Wernicke encephalopathy
default: Based on your symptoms and history, it appears you are experiencing Wernicke's encephalopathy, likely due to chronic alcohol use leading to thiamine (vitamin B1) deficiency. The damage to your mammillary bodies, nystagmus, and ataxia are characteristic of this condition. The recovery of most cognitive functions but persistent short-term memory deficits aligns with the typical outcomes of Wernicke's encephalopathy, which can lead to Korsakoff syndrome if not treated promptly. Continued support and rehabilitation may help improve your memory issues further.

question:
Four days after my admission to the hospital for a pulmonary contusion and whiplash injury from a motor vehicle collision, I began to experience severe pain in my right flank, accompanied by muscle spasms. I also felt nauseous and had two episodes of vomiting, along with noticeable abdominal bloating. Initially, my pain had been well managed with acetaminophen every six hours.

I have a history of umbilical hernia repair surgery from two years ago and take sertraline for depression. At the time of my assessment, my temperature was 36.5°C, pulse was 99 beats per minute, respirations were 17 breaths per minute, and my blood pressure was 102/72 mm Hg. After receiving 0.5 liters of crystalloid fluids, my blood pressure improved to 118/79 mm Hg.

Upon examination, multiple ecchymoses were observed on my anterior abdominal wall, following the course of a seatbelt, and I had additional ecchymoses on both flanks. My bowel sounds were absent, and I experienced tenderness in all four quadrants with voluntary guarding. I was informed that my hemoglobin level was low. An x-ray of my abdomen indicated changes that suggest a possible underlying issue requiring further evaluation.
options:
A. Small bowel perforation B. Intraabdominal adhesions C. Effect of pain medication D. Sigmoid volvulus E. Spinal cord injury F. Retroperitoneal hemorrhage G. Acute mesenteric ischemia
"
default:
Based on your symptoms and examination findings, it appears you may be experiencing complications related to your recent motor vehicle collision, particularly concerning your abdominal injuries. The severe right flank pain, muscle spasms, nausea, vomiting, abdominal bloating, and the presence of ecchymoses suggest possible internal bleeding or organ injury, such as a splenic or renal injury, especially given the mechanism of injury and the seatbelt-related bruising.

The absence of bowel sounds and tenderness with guarding indicate potential peritoneal irritation, which could suggest a more serious condition like hemoperitoneum or intra-abdominal hemorrhage. The low hemoglobin level further supports the possibility of significant internal bleeding.

Immediate further evaluation, likely including a CT scan of the abdomen, is warranted

question:
I am a 30-year-old man who recently started taking TMP-SMX for a urinary tract infection. I went to urgent care because I developed a new rash. When I arrived, my vital signs were taken; my blood pressure was 121/80 mm Hg, my pulse was 91 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 18 breaths per minute, and my temperature was 36.7°C (98.2°F). 

During the physical examination, the healthcare provider noted a desquamative skin condition affecting both of my lower extremities. I did not have any immediate discomfort, but the appearance of the rash was concerning to me. After the examination, my medical history and current medications were discussed to determine the possible cause of the rash. 

I was informed that additional tests, including a basic chemistry panel, would be performed to gather more information, although I did not receive any specific results at that time. Overall, I felt the need for a thorough evaluation due to the unexpected development of the rash following the initiation of my antibiotic therapy.
options: A. Dermatitis herpetiformis B. Steven-Johnson syndrome (SJS) C. Seborrheic dermatitis D. Atopic dermatitis E. Toxic epidermal necrolysis (TEN)
default:
The rash you developed after starting TMP-SMX (trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole) could be a drug reaction, such as a hypersensitivity reaction or an adverse effect of the medication. Desquamative skin conditions can be associated with drug eruptions, and TMP-SMX is known to cause skin reactions in some individuals. It's important to monitor for any additional symptoms, such as fever, itching, or systemic signs, which could indicate a more severe reaction like Stevens-Johnson syndrome or toxic epidermal necrolysis, although these are rare. 

Since you are undergoing further evaluation with a basic chemistry panel, the healthcare provider will likely assess your kidney function and electrolyte levels, as TMP-SMX can affect renal function. It’s

question:
I am a 17-year-old girl who was admitted to the emergency department due to severe retrosternal chest pain. The pain started suddenly after I vomited following a large meal. My parents mentioned that I have a very restricted diet and that I frequently induce vomiting after eating. 

When I arrived at the hospital, I felt pale and was in severe distress. The medical team checked my vital signs, which showed a blood pressure of 100/60 mm Hg, a heart rate of 98 beats per minute, a respiratory rate of 14 breaths per minute, and a temperature of 37.9℃ (100.2℉). During the examination, the doctors noted that my lungs were clear, but they heard a crunching, raspy sound over my chest that matched my heartbeat. My abdomen was soft and not tender, which the doctors took into account during their assessment. 

Given the circumstances and my symptoms, the medical team considered which tests would most likely confirm the diagnosis I was facing.
options: A. Upper endoscopy B. ECG C. Echocardiography D. Contrast esophagram E. Measurement of D-dimer
default:
Based on your symptoms and history, the medical team is likely considering a diagnosis of pneumomediastinum, possibly due to a rupture of the esophagus (Boerhaave syndrome) or a related condition. The crunching sound over your chest, known as Hamman's sign, is indicative of air in the mediastinum. 

To confirm the diagnosis, the most appropriate test would be a chest X-ray or a CT scan of the chest, which can help visualize air in the mediastinum and assess for any esophageal rupture or other complications.

question:
I am a 47-year-old man who recently visited the emergency department due to experiencing urinary and fecal incontinence for the past six hours. Earlier that day, I had fallen at my construction site and sustained injuries to my back and thighs, but I did not seek medical attention at that time. To manage my lower back pain, I took ibuprofen.

Upon arriving at the emergency department, my vital signs were taken, and I was found to have a temperature of 36.9°C, a pulse of 80 beats per minute, and blood pressure of 132/84 mm Hg. During the examination, the doctor noted tenderness over my lumbar spine and weakness in both lower extremities. They observed absent ankle jerk reflexes, while my patellar reflexes were still present. Additionally, I had decreased rectal tone, and an ultrasound of my bladder indicated that it was full.

Given these findings, the medical team began to consider potential diagnoses related to my condition.
options:
A. Spinal epidural abscess B. Cerebellar stroke C. Cauda equina syndrome D. Conus medullaris syndrome E. Anterior spinal cord syndrome F. Brown-Sequard syndrome
"
default: Based on your symptoms and examination findings, the most concerning diagnosis is cauda equina syndrome. This condition is characterized by urinary and fecal incontinence, lower extremity weakness, absent ankle reflexes, and decreased rectal tone, all of which you are experiencing. The recent fall and subsequent back pain may have led to a herniated disc or other spinal injury compressing the cauda equina. Immediate medical intervention is critical to prevent permanent neurological damage.

question:
I am a 22-year-old female software analyst who visited a medical clinic to evaluate some symptoms I had been experiencing. For the past two months, I noticed tingling and numbness in both of my hands. These sensations tend to worsen by the end of my workday, but I typically do not feel them on my days off.

I have been living with type I diabetes for the past two years, and I manage my condition with insulin. During my visit, I mentioned that I have been sexually active, but I have also been experiencing irregular periods for the last three months. To address the possibility of pregnancy, a urine pregnancy test was conducted, and the result came back negative.

I am seeking to understand what might be causing the tingling and numbness in my hands, especially considering my diabetes and the other health factors I described.
options: A. Hypothyroidism B. Acute intermittent porphyria C. Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis D. Diabetic neuropathy E. Multiple sclerosis
default:
The tingling and numbness in your hands, especially worsening by the end of your workday, could be related to several factors. Given your type I diabetes, one possibility is diabetic neuropathy, which can cause nerve damage leading to these sensations. However, since you mentioned that the symptoms improve on your days off, it may also be related to repetitive strain or posture issues, especially if you spend long hours typing or using a mouse.

Additionally, hormonal changes due to irregular periods could also contribute to these symptoms, as they can affect nerve function and circulation. It's important to discuss these symptoms with your healthcare provider, who may recommend further evaluation, such as nerve conduction studies or adjustments to your work ergonomics, to determine the exact cause and appropriate treatment

question:
I am a 17-year-old male and recently went to the emergency department due to pain in my left eye. For the past week, the pain has been progressively worsening. I have not noticed any changes in my vision, nor have I experienced difficulty moving my left eye. Additionally, I have not had any recent trauma to the area.

In my lifestyle, I smoke about one pack of cigarettes daily and drink alcohol socially. Over the past month, I have had unprotected sexual encounters with two males and four females. My current medications include loratadine, nasal saline spray, and diphenhydramine.

When I arrived at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 99.5°F, my blood pressure was 100/55 mmHg, my pulse was 72 beats per minute, and my respirations were 11 per minute. My oxygen saturation was measured at 98% on room air. 

During the physical examination, I was noted to be a healthy young man, and the cardiopulmonary exam was within normal limits. The exam revealed certain findings that were noted on a figure provided by the medical staff. The healthcare team discussed potential diagnoses based on my symptoms and examination results.
options: A. Obstruction of the nasolacrimal duct B. Staphylococcus aureus infection of the inferior rectus C. Sexually transmitted infection D. Thrombosis of a major vessel E. Infection of a hair follicle
default:
Given your symptoms of progressively worsening left eye pain without changes in vision or eye movement difficulties, along with your smoking history and recent unprotected sexual encounters, a few potential diagnoses could be considered. 

One possibility is **uveitis**, which can cause eye pain and may be associated with systemic conditions or infections. Another consideration could be **acute glaucoma**, especially if there are any signs of increased intraocular pressure, although this typically presents with vision changes. 

Infections, such as **herpes simplex keratitis**, could also be a concern, particularly given your sexual history. 

It's crucial to follow up with an eye specialist for a thorough examination and appropriate diagnostic tests to determine the exact cause of your symptoms.

question:
I am a 17-year-old rugby player, and I recently experienced an injury during a game. While running, I rolled my ankle, which caused me to limp into the emergency room for evaluation. The medical staff assessed my injury and noted that the mechanism of injury involved both ankle plantar flexion and inversion. 

During the examination, they checked for point tenderness around the medial and lateral malleolus, but there was none present. They performed an anterior drawer test on my ankle, which returned a positive result, indicating some instability. However, the talar tilt test was negative, suggesting that certain ligamentous structures were intact. 

Based on these findings, the medical team concluded that I likely sustained a specific type of ankle injury, although the exact nature of the injury was not detailed in the conversation. Overall, the experience left me concerned about my recovery and the impact this injury might have on my ability to play rugby in the future.
options: A. Anterior talofibular ligament (ATFL) sprain B. Calcaneofibular ligament (CFL) sprain C. Deltoid ligament sprain D. Tibia fracture E. Fibula fracture
default: Based on your description, it sounds like you may have sustained a lateral ankle sprain, likely involving the anterior talofibular ligament (ATFL), given the positive anterior drawer test indicating instability. The absence of point tenderness around the malleoli and a negative talar tilt test suggest that other ligaments, such as the calcaneofibular ligament, may still be intact. Recovery can vary, but with proper rehabilitation, many athletes return to their sport. It's important to follow your medical team's advice and focus on strengthening and stability exercises to aid your recovery.

question:
I am a 62-year-old man who went to the emergency department due to colicky pain in my lower abdomen and noticeable abdominal distension that had been occurring for the past 12 hours. I have a history of chronic constipation, for which I regularly take lactulose and senna laxatives. When I arrived at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 37.1°C (98.7°F), my blood pressure was 110/60 mm Hg, and my pulse was 85 beats per minute.

During the physical examination, the doctor observed diffuse abdominal distension and tenderness, and I noticed that my bowel sounds were faint. After these observations, I underwent a plain abdominal radiograph to assess my condition further. The medical team was evaluating the situation to determine the most likely diagnosis related to my symptoms.
options: A. Intussusception B. Infectious colitis C. Bowel adhesions D. Volvulus E. Acute diverticulitis
default: Based on your symptoms of colicky lower abdominal pain, noticeable abdominal distension, a history of chronic constipation, and faint bowel sounds, the most likely diagnosis is a bowel obstruction, possibly due to fecal impaction. The abdominal radiograph would likely show signs of distended bowel loops and possibly air-fluid levels, supporting this diagnosis.

question:
I am a 16-year-old girl, and I was brought to the physician by my mother because I have not yet had my menstrual period. At birth, I was diagnosed with partial labial fusion and clitoromegaly. My mother mentioned that during her pregnancy with me, she noticed abnormal hair growth on her chin. I have been experiencing severe acne, which has been quite distressing. 

Three years ago, I broke my wrist after a minor injury, and last year, I sustained a spinal compression fracture while lifting a box during a move. Currently, I am taking oral isotretinoin for my acne and an oral contraceptive. In terms of growth, I am at the 97th percentile for height and the 50th percentile for weight. 

During the physical examination, the doctor observed numerous inflamed pustules on my face and upper back. My breast development is at Tanner stage I. I chose not to undergo a pelvic examination. A pelvic ultrasound was performed, which revealed that I have multiple cysts on my ovaries and a normal uterus.

default:

1. **Delayed Menstruation**: You have not yet had your menstrual period, which is common in PCOS.
2. **Clitoromegaly and Labial Fusion**: These may suggest a possible androgen excess, which is often associated with PCOS.
3. **Severe Acne**: This is another symptom linked to elevated androgen levels.
4. **Ovarian Cysts**: The ultrasound findings of multiple cysts on your ovaries support the diagnosis of PCOS.

question:
I am a 72-year-old woman who visited the emergency department four hours after experiencing a sudden onset of a diffuse, dull, throbbing headache. Along with the headache, I noticed blurred vision, nausea, and had one episode of vomiting. My medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus, for which I take hydrochlorothiazide, lisinopril, atorvastatin, and metformin. 

I have been a smoker for 30 years, consuming one pack of cigarettes daily, and I drink 1 to 2 glasses of wine each day. Upon arrival at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 36.6 °C (97.9 °F), my pulse was 90 beats per minute, my respirations were 14 per minute, and my blood pressure was elevated at 185/110 mm Hg. 

During the examination, the doctor performed a fundoscopic examination, which revealed bilateral blurring of the optic disc margins. The physical and neurologic examinations showed no other abnormalities. Additionally, a complete blood count and serum tests for electrolytes, urea nitrogen, and creatinine were found to be within the reference range. A urinalysis indicated 2+ protein but did not show the presence of white blood cells or red blood cells.
options:
A. Ischemic stroke B. Subarachnoid hemorrhage C. Idiopathic intracranial hypertension D. Migraine headache E. Hypertensive emergency F. Transient ischemic attack G. Giant cell arteritis
"
default:
Based on the symptoms and findings you've described, it appears that you may be experiencing a hypertensive crisis, potentially leading to hypertensive encephalopathy. The sudden onset of a severe headache, blurred vision, nausea, vomiting, and elevated blood pressure (185/110 mm Hg) are concerning for this condition. The bilateral blurring of the optic disc margins observed during the fundoscopic examination suggests possible papilledema, which can occur due to increased intracranial pressure.

The presence of protein in the urinalysis, along with your history of hypertension and diabetes, raises the possibility of renal involvement or a hypertensive emergency. question:
I am a 24-year-old man who went to the emergency department due to worsening shortness of breath and an intermittent cough that produced blood-tinged sputum over the past 10 days. During this period, I experienced three episodes of blood in my urine. 

I had been diagnosed with latent tuberculosis six years ago after a positive tuberculin skin test and received treatment at that time. I do not take any medications currently. My family history includes my maternal aunt, who has systemic lupus erythematosus. 

Upon examination in the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 37°C (98.6°F), my pulse was 92 beats per minute, and my respirations were elevated at 28 breaths per minute. My blood pressure was measured at 152/90 mm Hg. The doctor noted diffuse crackles in both lung bases during the examination. 

I underwent several tests, including blood and urine analyses, and a chest X-ray, which showed patchy pulmonary infiltrates in both lungs. Additionally, a renal biopsy revealed linear deposits of IgG along the glomerular basement membrane. These findings were concerning, and I was informed that further evaluation was necessary to determine the most likely diagnosis.
options:
A. Goodpasture syndrome B. Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis C. IgA nephropathy D. Granulomatosis with polyangiitis E. Reactivated tuberculosis F. Microscopic polyangiitis G. Lupus nephritis
"
default: Based on the symptoms and findings you've described, the most likely diagnosis is Goodpasture syndrome. This condition is characterized by the presence of anti-glomerular basement membrane antibodies, leading to pulmonary hemorrhage (evidenced by your cough with blood-tinged sputum and diffuse crackles) and glomerulonephritis (indicated by the episodes of blood in your urine and the renal biopsy showing linear IgG deposits). The history of latent tuberculosis and family history of systemic lupus erythematosus may also contribute to the complexity of your case, but the combination of respiratory and renal symptoms strongly points towards Goodpasture syndrome.

question:
I visited the emergency department due to severe abdominal pain that I had developed 12 hours prior. The pain was constant and I rated it a 7 out of 10. Alongside the pain, I experienced nausea and had vomited twice. In the last four hours, I had two episodes of nonbloody diarrhea, and I have a 12-month history of intermittent constipation.

I do not have any sick contacts or a history of recent travel. My past medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, mild intermittent asthma, and allergic rhinitis. My diet mainly consists of high-fat foods, and I do not smoke; I drink 1 to 2 glasses of wine per week and do not use illicit drugs. My current medications include lisinopril, metformin, an albuterol inhaler, fexofenadine, and psyllium husk fiber. I have no known drug allergies.

During the physical examination, I was lying back in the hospital bed and appeared uncomfortable. My temperature was elevated at 38.4°C (101.1°F). The examination revealed tenderness in the left lower quadrant of my abdomen, but there was no guarding or rebound tenderness. My extremities showed no edema, and I was alert and oriented throughout the assessment.
options: A. Ischemic colitis B. Crohn disease C. Cholecystitis D. Irritable bowel syndrome E. Appendicitis F. Ulcerative colitis G. Diverticulitis
default: Based on your symptoms and examination findings, you may be experiencing acute diverticulitis. The severe abdominal pain, particularly in the left lower quadrant, along with fever, nausea, vomiting, and diarrhea, aligns with this diagnosis. Your history of intermittent constipation and high-fat diet could contribute to the development of diverticular disease. It is advisable to undergo further imaging, such as a CT scan of the abdomen, to confirm the diagnosis and assess the severity of the condition. Treatment typically involves antibiotics and dietary modifications, and in some cases, surgical intervention may be necessary.

question:
I am a 55-year-old man who recently visited the office for an eye exam. Over the past few weeks, I have experienced some difficulty seeing, although I have not felt any pain associated with my vision changes. I have a history of HIV, which I was diagnosed with about 20 years ago due to my intravenous drug use. I stopped using drugs 10 years ago, but I have not been consistent with my medication regimen.

During my visit, the healthcare provider noted that my last CD4+ count was 42, recorded six months prior. My vital signs were within normal ranges, and I underwent a fundoscopic exam as part of the eye examination. The results showed that I have experienced some loss of both central and peripheral vision. The provider discussed potential diagnoses related to my symptoms and medical history.
options: A. Retinal vein occlusion B. Retinal detachment C. Acute angle closure glaucoma D. CMV retinitis E. HSV retinitis
default: Given your history of HIV, a very low CD4+ count, and the vision changes you've experienced, it's crucial to consider the possibility of opportunistic infections or conditions associated with advanced HIV. One significant concern is cytomegalovirus (CMV) retinitis, which can lead to vision loss and is common in individuals with severely compromised immune systems. Other potential diagnoses could include retinal detachment or other retinal diseases. It's essential to follow up with an ophthalmologist for further evaluation and management, as timely treatment can help preserve vision.

question:
I am a 45-year-old woman who has been concerned about my inguinal hernia. Two months ago, I went to the emergency department because I noticed a swelling in my left lower abdomen. The doctors at the hospital were able to easily reduce the mass and referred me to the general surgery clinic for an elective surgical repair. Since my condition was not deemed urgent, I was placed on a waiting list for surgery.

Despite this reassurance, I find myself repeatedly visiting the clinic and the emergency department, anxious that my bowels might be trapped and dying. Each time I go, the medical staff reassures me, and any protrusion is quickly reduced. In addition to my hernia concerns, I have a history of abdominal pain and inconsistent bowel habits, which I have discussed with my primary care physician multiple times. However, no specific cause has been identified for these symptoms.

I continue to experience intermittent abdominal discomfort and spend several hours each day worrying about my health and what might be happening to me. I do not have any other significant medical history, but the ongoing anxiety about my condition has been challenging to manage.
options: A. Conversion disorder B. Malingering disorder C. Factitious disorder D. Illness anxiety disorder E. Somatic symptom disorder
default:
It sounds like you're experiencing significant anxiety related to your inguinal hernia and associated abdominal symptoms. While it's understandable to be concerned about your health, especially with a history of abdominal pain and bowel issues, it's important to focus on managing your anxiety and finding ways to cope while you wait for surgery.

Consider discussing your anxiety with your primary care physician or a mental health professional. They can help you explore strategies such as cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT), mindfulness techniques, or medication if appropriate. Additionally, maintaining open communication with your surgical team about your concerns may provide further reassurance and support.

In the meantime, try to engage in activities that distract you from your worries and promote relaxation. Prioritizing self-care can also help alleviate some of

question:
I am a 72-year-old man who was involved in a traffic collision. After the accident, I was transported to the emergency room by ambulance. Upon arrival, I was in shock and comatose. The medical team examined me and noted a heart rate of 60 beats per minute and a blood pressure of 70 over 40 mm Hg. Despite their resuscitative efforts, I did not survive.

Following my death, an autopsy was performed, which revealed multiple internal hemorrhages and signs of ischemic damage in my lungs, kidneys, and brain. The examination of my heart showed significant anomalies. The medical staff suggested that acute hypovolemia was likely the cause of the ischemic changes observed in my organs. However, they were also interested in understanding the underlying reason for the gross anomaly found in my heart.
options: A. Aortic valve regurgitation B. Mitral valve stenosis C. Senile calcific aortic stenosis D. Accumulation of amyloid in the myocardium E. Genetic mutation
default: The gross anomalies found in your heart during the autopsy could be indicative of underlying cardiovascular disease, which is common in older adults. Potential causes may include coronary artery disease, which can lead to ischemia, or structural abnormalities such as cardiomyopathy or valvular heart disease. These conditions can compromise blood flow and contribute to acute hypovolemia and subsequent ischemic damage to vital organs. The combination of these factors likely played a significant role in your critical condition following the traffic collision.

Upon arrival, I was found to have a fever, with an oral temperature of 103.6 degrees Fahrenheit. My vital signs were otherwise stable. During the physical examination, the doctor noted some unusual lesions on my skin that I had never seen before. Additionally, I experienced subtle weakness on the right side of my body, which affected both my upper and lower extremities.

While in the emergency room, I underwent various tests. The healthcare team informed me that my blood counts were concerning, particularly my hemoglobin level, which was significantly low. The right-sided weakness indicates a possible neurological issue, which could be due to a stroke or other central nervous system involvement.

question:
I am a 60-year-old woman who recently went to the emergency department because I had been experiencing progressive shortness of breath and a dry cough for the past week. I noticed that my symptoms worsened with physical activity but improved when I rested. 

Two years ago, I was diagnosed with chronic kidney disease, and I had just started regular dialysis treatment. When I arrived at the emergency department, my pulse rate was measured at 105 beats per minute, my blood pressure was 110 over 70 mm Hg, my respiratory rate was 30 breaths per minute, and my temperature was 37.8°C (100.0°F). 

During the respiratory examination, the doctor noted dullness on percussion, decreased vocal tactile fremitus, and decreased breath sounds over the base of my right lung. The remainder of the physical exam was normal. 

I am uncertain about the exact cause of my symptoms, but I am here seeking help for my condition.
options: A. Primary spontaneous pneumothorax (PSP) B. Pleural effusion C. Pulmonary tuberculosis (TB) D. Pneumonia E. Acute bronchitis
default: Based on your symptoms and examination findings, it is likely that you are experiencing a pleural effusion, particularly on the right side. The dullness on percussion, decreased tactile fremitus, and decreased breath sounds suggest fluid accumulation in the pleural space, which can cause shortness of breath and cough, especially with exertion. Given your history of chronic kidney disease and recent initiation of dialysis, fluid overload could be a contributing factor. It is important to follow up with your healthcare provider for further evaluation, which may include imaging studies like a chest X-ray or ultrasound, and possibly a thoracentesis to analyze the pleural fluid.

question:
I was taken to the physician for a follow-up examination after experiencing recurrent asthma attacks. My mother mentioned that I had been having mild abdominal pain for the past two weeks. At the time of the visit, I was using daily inhaled fluticasone and inhaled albuterol as needed for my asthma.

During the examination, the physician noted that I appeared well. My temperature was measured at 37°C, my pulse was 100 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was recorded at 130/85 mm Hg. The doctor listened to my lungs and found them clear, with no signs of murmurs, rubs, or gallops in my heart. 

When it came to my abdomen, the doctor found a smooth, nontender mass on the left side that did not cross the midline. The rest of the examination showed no abnormalities. The physician also reviewed some lab results, which indicated that my complete blood count and serum concentrations of electrolytes, urea nitrogen, and creatinine were all within the reference range. 

Overall, I felt comfortable during the visit, but the physician was concerned about the abdominal mass and the ongoing mild pain.
options:
A. Polycystic kidney disease B. Lymphoma C. Acute leukemia D. Wilms' tumor E. Neuroblastoma F. Renal cell carcinoma G. Ovarian cyst
"
default: The presence of a smooth, nontender abdominal mass on the left side, along with mild abdominal pain, raises concern for a potential underlying condition. Given your age and the characteristics of the mass, one possibility could be an enlarged spleen (splenomegaly) or a renal mass, such as a cyst or tumor. Other considerations might include lymphadenopathy or a gastrointestinal issue, but the lack of tenderness and normal lab results may suggest a less acute process. Further imaging, such as an ultrasound or CT scan, would be warranted to evaluate the mass and determine the appropriate next steps in management.

question:
I am a 49-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department by ambulance due to sudden-onset chest pain. This pain began while I was having dinner about two hours prior. The discomfort was substernal and radiated into my neck and down my left arm. 

I have a medical history that includes hypercholesterolemia, which I manage with statin therapy, and coronary artery disease. Upon arrival at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 37.0°C (98.6°F). My blood pressure was noted to be 155/90 mm Hg, my pulse was 112 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate was 25 breaths per minute. 

The medical staff conducted tests, including measuring my troponin I levels, which were elevated. Additionally, they performed a 12-lead ECG to gather more information about my condition. Based on my symptoms and medical history, the healthcare team began assessing the likely cause of my presentation.
options: A. Coronary vasospasm B. Left main coronary artery occlusion C. Left circumflex artery occlusion D. Left anterior descending artery occlusion E. Right main coronary artery occlusion
default: Based on your symptoms of sudden-onset substernal chest pain radiating to the neck and left arm, along with your history of coronary artery disease and elevated troponin I levels, it is highly likely that you are experiencing an acute myocardial infarction (heart attack). The elevated troponin indicates myocardial injury, and your vital signs suggest possible stress on the cardiovascular system. Immediate evaluation and treatment, including possible angiography and revascularization, are critical in this situation.

options: A. Cholecystitis B. Pancreatitis C. Choledocholithiasis D. Duodenal peptic ulcer E. Gallbladder cancer

Throughout my adult life, I have experienced frequent lung infections, with the most recent one occurring two weeks ago. I have had hematuria on two previous occasions, but the severity I experienced this time was unprecedented.

question:
I am a 10-month-old infant who was brought in by my parents due to concerns about my health. I had been vomiting multiple times over the past couple of hours, and my most recent vomit was green in color. My parents mentioned that I had not passed any stool during this time. 

Upon arrival at the medical facility, I was examined by a healthcare professional. During the examination, I was found to be irritable and crying. The doctor palpated my abdomen and discovered an abdominal mass in the periumbilical region. 

Given these findings, an emergency laparotomy was performed to investigate further. The procedure revealed that a part of my intestine had folded into the section adjacent to it. This condition led to my symptoms and required immediate medical intervention.
options: A. Hirschsprung’s disease B. Meckel’s diverticulum C. Duodenal atresia D. Pyloric stenosis E. Intussusception
default: Based on the symptoms and findings described, you are likely experiencing intussusception, a condition where a part of the intestine telescopes into an adjacent segment. This can cause obstruction, leading to vomiting (especially bilious, or green, vomit), abdominal pain, irritability, and a palpable abdominal mass. The emergency laparotomy was necessary to address the obstruction and prevent further complications.

question:
I arrived at the emergency department due to severe pain and swelling in the proximal joint of my right hand's third finger. This pain was so intense that it woke me from sleep earlier that morning. I had never experienced anything like this before. 

For the past 25 years, I have been smoking about a pack of cigarettes daily and consuming alcohol heavily on weekends. Last night, I attended a party where I drank 3 to 4 beers and was unable to drive home afterward. I do not have any significant past medical history, but my family health history includes my mother, who passed away from pancreatic cancer at 55, and my father, who died from a stroke two years ago.

When I was examined, my temperature was noted at 37.7°C, with a blood pressure of 130/70 mm Hg and a pulse rate of 104 beats per minute. I was in moderate distress from the pain. The examination revealed that the proximal interphalangeal joint of my third finger was very tender, swollen, warm, and slightly red. Due to the extreme tenderness, the range of motion could not be assessed. 

A synovial fluid aspiration was performed on the joint, and the findings included cloudy, dense yellow fluid with a high white blood cell count and negatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals.
options: A. Pseudogout B. Chronic gout C. Septic arthritis D. Acute gout E. Reactive arthritis
default:
The clinical presentation and synovial fluid analysis suggest that you are experiencing an acute gout attack. The key findings include:

- Severe pain and swelling in the proximal interphalangeal joint of the third finger.
- Cloudy, dense yellow synovial fluid with a high white blood cell count.
- The presence of negatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals, which are characteristic of monosodium urate crystals found in gout.

Given your history of heavy alcohol consumption and smoking, both of which can contribute to hyperuricemia, this aligns with the diagnosis of gout. Treatment typically involves nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), colchicine, or corticosteroids to manage the acute attack, along with lifestyle modifications to prevent future episodes.

question:
I am a 22-year-old man who went to the emergency department due to pain and swelling in my left knee. This occurred one day after I injured it while playing soccer. While sprinting on the field, I slipped while trying to kick the ball and landed on the front of my knee.

In my medical history, I had an appendectomy when I was 16 years old. Upon arrival at the emergency department, my vital signs were within normal limits. The examination revealed that my left knee was swollen and tender, and I experienced limited range of motion due to pain. The tibial tuberosity was also tender to touch. When force was applied to the proximal tibia after flexing my knee, it was noted that the left tibia was displaced posteriorly. The rest of the examination showed no other abnormalities.

An x-ray of my left knee joint was performed, which indicated an avulsion fracture of the tibial condyle. The medical team is now considering the most likely diagnosis based on these findings.
options: A. Anterior cruciate ligament injury B. Lateral meniscus injury C. Posterior cruciate ligament injury D. Lateral collateral ligament injury E. Medial meniscus injury F. Medial collateral ligament injury
default: Based on the provided information, the most likely diagnosis is an **avulsion fracture of the anterior cruciate ligament (ACL)** at the tibial attachment. The mechanism of injury during soccer, the tenderness at the tibial tuberosity, and the posterior displacement of the tibia suggest that the injury is related to the ACL, which can be associated with avulsion fractures in young athletes.

question:
I am a 78-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department by my son after I recently fell. I complained of pain in my ribs and had been feeling less responsive than usual. Additionally, I had been experiencing diarrhea. I live alone in my apartment and have a history of hypertension and dementia. My current medications include lisinopril for my blood pressure, as well as memantine and donepezil for my cognitive condition.

default:
Based on the information provided, the patient is a 78-year-old man with a history of hypertension and dementia, presenting with confusion, unsteady gait, nystagmus, and recent falls. The presence of diarrhea, scattered bruises, and fragile hair raises concern for possible underlying issues, such as dehydration, electrolyte imbalances, or nutritional deficiencies.

The neurological symptoms, including confusion and inappropriate responses, could be attributed to dehydration, a urinary tract infection, or a possible stroke, especially given the systolic murmur and crackles in the lungs, which may suggest heart failure or pulmonary edema.

question:

Based on the clinical presentation, the patient is likely experiencing an infectious process, possibly pneumonia, given the fever, productive cough, and crackles in the left lower lobe. The presence of petechiae and purpura raises concern for a hematological issue, potentially related to his history of myelodysplastic syndrome (MDS) and recent chemotherapy, which can lead to thrombocytopenia and increased susceptibility to infections.

The enlarged lymph nodes suggest a possible lymphoproliferative disorder or an infectious etiology, such as a viral or bacterial infection. question:

This morning, I coughed up blood for the first time, despite having a persistent cough for the past three weeks. default:
Given your symptoms—coughing up blood, persistent cough, hoarseness, and the finding of a rough vegetating lesion on your vocal cord—there are several concerning possibilities, particularly considering your smoking history. 

The lesion could potentially be a vocal cord polyp, but more alarmingly, it raises the suspicion of laryngeal cancer, especially in a smoker. The presence of blood in your cough (hemoptysis) is particularly worrisome and warrants further investigation.

Next steps typically include:

1. **Referral to an ENT specialist**: They may perform a more detailed examination, possibly including a biopsy of the lesion to determine its nature.

question:
I recently visited the physician for a well-child examination, as I had some concerns about my weight. At 17 years old, I often find myself at buffet restaurants, but I usually feel guilty about my eating choices afterward. I also have a history of burning my extremities with cigarettes, which I know is not a healthy behavior. 

My last menstrual period occurred three weeks ago. I am currently in high school and play field hockey on the school team, which keeps me active. During the examination, the doctor noted that I am in the 25th percentile for height, the 12th percentile for weight, and the 17th percentile for BMI. 

During the physical exam, the doctor observed bilateral enlargement of my parotid glands. They also examined my mouth and found signs of perimolysis. Fortunately, the rest of the examination did not reveal any other abnormalities. After discussing my symptoms and concerns, the physician considered my situation and indicated that there are potential diagnoses that could explain my symptoms.
options:
A. Major depressive disorder B. Kleine-Levin syndrome C. Binge eating disorder D. Bulimia nervosa E. Obsessive compulsive disorder F. Borderline personality disorder G. Body dysmorphic disorder H. Anorexia nervosa
"
default: Based on your symptoms and the findings from your examination, it appears that you may be experiencing signs consistent with bulimia nervosa. The bilateral enlargement of the parotid glands and perimolysis (enamel erosion) are often associated with frequent vomiting, which can occur in individuals with this eating disorder. Your concerns about weight, feelings of guilt after eating, and the context of your eating habits at buffet restaurants further support this possibility. It’s important to discuss these findings with your physician for a comprehensive evaluation and to explore appropriate treatment options.

question:
I am 57 years old and recently experienced two days of severe, generalized abdominal pain that worsened after meals. Along with the pain, I felt nauseated and noticed that I had occasional diarrhea, which was mixed with blood. My medical history is mostly unremarkable, aside from having essential hypertension. 

During this time, my vital signs were taken: my temperature was 36.9°C (98.4°F), my blood pressure was measured at 145/92 mm Hg, and my pulse was irregular, at 105 beats per minute. When examined physically, the doctor noted mild tenderness around my belly button. The combination of these symptoms raised concerns, and I was informed that further evaluation was necessary to determine the cause of my condition.
options: A. Acute pancreatitis B. Crohn's disease C. Acute mesenteric ischemia D. Diverticular disease E. Gastroenteritis
default: Given your symptoms of severe abdominal pain, nausea, diarrhea with blood, and the irregular pulse, it is crucial to seek immediate medical evaluation. These signs could indicate a serious gastrointestinal issue, such as an inflammatory condition (like diverticulitis or colitis), a possible gastrointestinal bleed, or even an obstruction. The irregular pulse and elevated blood pressure may suggest a stress response or underlying cardiovascular concerns. Prompt diagnostic imaging and laboratory tests are essential to identify the underlying cause and initiate appropriate treatment. Please follow up with your healthcare provider urgently.

question:
