I have a medical history that includes diabetes and hypertension, but I am not currently on any medications for these conditions. When I arrived at the emergency department, my vital signs were taken. My temperature was 97.5°F, my blood pressure was recorded at 173/101 mmHg, my pulse was 82 beats per minute, my respirations were 14 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was measured at 98% while breathing room air.

During the physical examination, the healthcare provider noted that my breath sounds were clear and an S4 heart sound was present. Additionally, a rectal examination revealed a firm and nodular prostate, which was non-tender. A fecal occult sample was taken, and it tested negative for blood. 

I am now awaiting further evaluation to determine the cause of my syncope and the implications of my symptoms.
options: A. Benign prostatic hyperplasia B. Normal physical exam C. Prostate abscess D. Prostate cancer E. Prostatitis
default:
Given your age, medical history of diabetes and hypertension, and the recent episode of syncope, several factors need to be considered. The elevated blood pressure (173/101 mmHg) suggests poorly controlled hypertension, which can contribute to syncope, especially if there are fluctuations in blood pressure. The presence of an S4 heart sound may indicate left ventricular hypertrophy or diastolic dysfunction, often associated with long-standing hypertension.

The firm and nodular prostate raises concerns that may warrant further evaluation, particularly for benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) or other conditions, but it is less likely to be directly related to your syncope.

The negative fecal occult blood test is reassuring regarding gastrointestinal bleeding, but it does not rule out other causes of

question:
I was 19 years old when I was taken to the emergency department by ambulance due to unusual behavior that began three hours earlier at a party. I have a history of major depressive disorder and seasonal allergies, and my mother has a history of anxiety. On weekends, I typically drink about five beers. At the time, I was taking amitriptyline and diphenhydramine.

Upon arrival, I was not responding to questions and kept saying, "The government is following me everywhere." My vital signs showed a temperature of 37.9°C, a pulse of 115 beats per minute, respirations at 24 per minute, and a blood pressure of 160/89 mm Hg. I was sweating profusely and appeared disoriented, unable to recognize where I was or what time it was. During the neurologic examination, it was noted that my pupils were dilated, and I exhibited hyperreflexia. My feet felt cold, and the capillary refill time was noted to be three seconds.

At one point, I became agitated, screaming and attempting to bite the physician. A urine toxicology screening was conducted, which tested positive for ethyl glucuronide. This experience was distressing and confusing for me, and I was unable to understand what was happening.
options: A. Brief psychotic disorder B. Neuroleptic malignant syndrome C. Anticholinergic toxicity D. Delirium tremens E. Lysergic acid diethylamide intoxication F. Synthetic cathinone intoxication
default: Based on the symptoms and history provided, it appears you may be experiencing an acute episode of anticholinergic toxicity, likely exacerbated by the combination of amitriptyline (a tricyclic antidepressant with anticholinergic properties) and diphenhydramine (an antihistamine with anticholinergic effects). The signs of confusion, agitation, dilated pupils, hyperreflexia, and elevated vital signs align with this condition. Additionally, the use of alcohol may have further complicated your situation, potentially leading to increased sedation or exacerbation of the anticholinergic effects. Immediate medical intervention would be necessary to manage these symptoms and ensure safety.

question: Two days after I gave birth to my son at home, I noticed that he was experiencing bilious vomiting. He seemed unable to pass meconium, and I observed that his abdomen was distended. Concerned about his condition, I decided to take him to the pediatric emergency room for evaluation. The medical team conducted an endoscopic biopsy of his proximal colon. This procedure revealed an absence of Meissner’s and Auerbach’s plexi in the bowel wall. After the examination, I learned that this information would help in determining the most likely diagnosis for my son’s symptoms.
options: A. Hirschsprung’s disease B. Ileocecal intussusception C. Meckel’s diverticulum D. Juvenile polyposis syndrome E. Volvulus of the sigmoid colon
default: Based on the symptoms you described—bilious vomiting, inability to pass meconium, abdominal distension, and the biopsy findings of absent Meissner’s and Auerbach’s plexi—the most likely diagnosis for your son is Hirschsprung's disease (congenital aganglionic megacolon). This condition is characterized by the absence of ganglion cells in the bowel, leading to obstruction and difficulty in passing stool.

question:
I am a 24-year-old woman who went to the emergency department due to a severe headache. The pain was at an intensity of 10 out of 10 and became worse when I chewed. I described the sensation as a dull pain located on the sides of my head. 

I am generally healthy and am not currently taking any medications. During the examination, my temperature was recorded at 97.0°F, blood pressure was 111/74 mmHg, my pulse was 83 beats per minute, my respirations were 13 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 98% while breathing room air. 

The physical exam revealed pain and tenderness in the mandibular and temporal regions, which intensified when I opened and closed my mouth.
options: A. Migraine headache B. Subarachnoid hemorrhage C. Temporal arteritis D. Temporomandibular joint dysfunction E. Tension headache
default: Based on your symptoms and examination findings, you may be experiencing temporomandibular joint (TMJ) dysfunction or possibly temporal arteritis, especially given the severe headache and tenderness in the temporal region. However, the age and general health suggest TMJ dysfunction is more likely. It would be advisable to follow up with a healthcare provider for further evaluation and management.

question:
I am a 31-year-old woman, and I recently visited my gynecologist for a routine well-visit. During the appointment, I discussed my sexual activity, as I am currently active with multiple male partners. For contraception, I use an intrauterine device. 

I mentioned that my last menstrual period occurred two weeks ago, and I did not report any abnormal vaginal discharge or sensations of burning or itching. The pelvic exam conducted during the visit was normal. However, the routine Pap smear taken during this appointment indicated some abnormalities. 

My gynecologist noted the findings and mentioned that they would evaluate the results further to determine the most likely organism responsible for the abnormal Pap smear. I am awaiting additional information regarding the next steps in addressing the results.
options: A. Treponema pallidum B. Chlamydia trachomatis C. Herpes simplex virus 1 D. Human papillomavirus E. Trichomonas vaginalis
default: It sounds like your gynecologist is taking the appropriate steps to evaluate the abnormal Pap smear results. Abnormalities can be caused by various factors, including infections (like HPV), inflammation, or precancerous changes. It's important to follow up on the results and any recommended tests or treatments. Make sure to discuss any concerns you have during your next appointment, and don’t hesitate to ask about the implications of the findings and the next steps in management.

question:
I am a 60-year-old man with a history of osteoarthritis, and I have been waiting for hip replacement surgery for three years. During my recent annual physical, I discussed my ongoing struggles with pain management. Despite taking over-the-counter pain medications, I still experience constant pain that is not alleviated by any analgesics. 

As part of my examination, my doctor assessed my renal function, which has shown deterioration compared to my last visit two years ago. I learned that my serum creatinine level is at 2.0 mg/dL, and a urinalysis indicated 1+ proteinuria, though there were no abnormalities seen under microscopy of the urine. Following this, I underwent a renal biopsy, which revealed eosinophilic infiltration and diffuse parenchymal inflammation. 

I am aware that these findings suggest a significant issue with my renal function, and I am seeking to understand the most likely explanation for this deterioration.
options: A. Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis B. Ischemic acute tubular necrosis C. Nephrotoxic acute tubular necrosis D. Toxic tubulointerstitial nephritis E. Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis
default: The deterioration in your renal function, indicated by the elevated serum creatinine level and the findings from the renal biopsy showing eosinophilic infiltration and diffuse parenchymal inflammation, suggests a possible diagnosis of acute interstitial nephritis (AIN). This condition can be caused by various factors, including medications, infections, or autoimmune processes. Given your history of osteoarthritis and the use of over-the-counter pain medications, particularly nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), it is plausible that these medications may have contributed to the renal impairment. AIN can lead to proteinuria and renal dysfunction, which aligns with your current symptoms and biopsy results. It is important to discuss these findings with your healthcare provider to determine the best course of action for managing both

question:
I am a 54-year-old man who recently visited the emergency department due to abdominal distension that had persisted for the past three weeks. Along with the distension, I experienced generalized abdominal discomfort, nausea, and a decreased appetite. 

Three months ago, I had undergone an inguinal hernia repair, which did not result in any complications. My medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus, congestive heart failure, and untreated hepatitis C. At the time of my visit, I was taking several medications, including aspirin, atorvastatin, metoprolol, lisinopril, and metformin. 

I have a family history of alcoholic liver disease, my father having been affected. I smoked one pack of cigarettes daily for 30 years but quit five years ago. I also consumed 3 to 4 beers daily. During the examination, I appeared cachectic, but my vital signs were within normal limits. 

The physical examination revealed a distended abdomen with shifting dullness, yet there was no tenderness or palpable masses. There was a well-healed surgical scar from my previous procedure, and I had mild bilateral lower extremity nonpitting edema. Following this, a diagnostic paracentesis was performed to analyze the fluid. 

At this point, I await further results to determine the cause of my symptoms.
options: A. Recent surgery B. Lymphoma C. Infection with M. tuberculosis D. Liver cirrhosis E. Infection with gram-positive bacteria F. Nephrotic syndrome G. Acute decompensated heart failure
default: Based on your symptoms and medical history, the abdominal distension and discomfort, along with the presence of shifting dullness, suggest the possibility of ascites. Given your history of untreated hepatitis C, alcohol use, and cachexia, liver disease, potentially leading to cirrhosis, is a likely underlying cause. The paracentesis will help determine the nature of the fluid (e.g., transudative vs. exudative) and may provide insights into whether the ascites is due to portal hypertension or another etiology. It's crucial to follow up on the results to guide further management.

question:
I am a 72-year-old man who recently visited my primary care provider for a checkup. Three months ago, blood work had shown that I had lymphocytosis. During this visit, I mentioned that I have been feeling a bit more tired than usual, although I did not report any other symptoms. My medical history includes hypertension and hyperlipidemia, for which I take lisinopril, hydrochlorothiazide, and atorvastatin. Three years ago, I underwent a hip replacement due to osteoarthritis. 

I do not have any significant family history of medical issues, and I drink alcohol socially but do not smoke. During the examination, my heart rate was 95 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 17 breaths per minute, and my blood pressure measured 135 over 85 mm Hg. My temperature was within normal limits at 36.8°C (98.2°F). Overall, I appeared well during the physical exam. My heartbeat had a regular rate and rhythm, and my lungs were clear. However, there was mild lymphadenopathy noted in my cervical lymph nodes. 

A complete blood count was performed, and I was informed that a specimen would be sent for flow cytometry analysis, which revealed a certain population that was CD 5, 19, 20, and 23 positive.
options: A. Aplastic anemia B. Chronic lymphocytic leukemia C. Tuberculosis D. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia E. Immune thrombocytopenic purpura
default: The findings from your flow cytometry analysis, particularly the presence of a population of cells that are CD5, CD19, CD20, and CD23 positive, are suggestive of a chronic lymphoproliferative disorder, most commonly chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL). The lymphocytosis and mild lymphadenopathy you experienced further support this possibility. Given your age and the symptoms of increased fatigue, it would be important to follow up with a hematologist for further evaluation and management.

question:
I am a 32-year-old woman, currently 35 weeks pregnant with my second child. I was admitted to the hospital about an hour after my membranes spontaneously ruptured. For the past day, I had been experiencing mild abdominal discomfort and nausea. My pregnancy has been complicated by gestational diabetes, which I manage with a strict diet.

I previously delivered my first child via a lower segment transverse cesarean section due to placental abruption. At the hospital, I was given iron and vitamin supplements, and I confirmed that my immunizations are current. Upon arrival, my temperature was recorded at 38.6°C, my pulse was 122 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was 110/78 mm Hg. 

During the abdominal examination, I was found to have severe tenderness throughout my lower quadrants. A speculum examination confirmed the rupture of membranes, with a drainage of malodorous, blood-tinged fluid. An ultrasound showed that the fetus was in a cephalic presentation, with a fetal heart rate of 175 beats per minute, which was reactive and showed no decelerations. 

These findings were concerning and indicated that I was experiencing complications related to my pregnancy.
options:
A. Influenza B. Chorioamnionitis C. Acute appendicitis D. Normal labor E. Acute pyelonephritis F. Uterine rupture
"
default: Based on your symptoms and findings, it appears you may be experiencing chorioamnionitis, an infection of the amniotic fluid and membranes, especially given the fever, tachycardia, and malodorous fluid. This condition is more common in cases of prolonged rupture of membranes and can pose risks to both you and your baby. Immediate management typically involves intravenous antibiotics and close monitoring, and depending on the clinical situation, early delivery may be considered to prevent further complications. It's crucial to discuss these findings with your healthcare team for appropriate intervention.

question:
I am a 52-year-old man who recently experienced a concerning health issue. Five weeks ago, I noticed multiple ulcers developing on my left forearm and neck after returning from a two-month stay in rural Peru. At the time, I did not recall any trauma or insect bites that might have caused these lesions. 

Initially, the lesions appeared as non-itchy red papules, which gradually enlarged and ulcerated, eventually forming crusts. During this period, I did not experience any fever or abdominal pain. Since my marriage at 24, I have been sexually active with a single partner.

When I sought medical attention, a physical examination revealed the lesions to be erythematous, crusted plaques with central ulcerations and raised borders. There were no signs of fluctuance, drainage, or sporotrichoid spread. To better understand the condition, a punch biopsy was performed. The results indicated an ulcerated lesion with a mixed inflammatory infiltrate and showed amastigotes within dermal macrophages when stained with Giemsa. 

I am now awaiting further information regarding the most likely diagnosis based on these findings.
options: A. Histoplasmosis B. Cutaneous leishmaniasis C. Ecthyma D. Syphilis E. Cutaneous tuberculosis
default: Based on your symptoms, travel history, and biopsy results showing amastigotes within dermal macrophages, the most likely diagnosis is cutaneous leishmaniasis. This condition is often associated with exposure to sandfly bites in endemic areas, such as rural Peru. The lesions you described align with the typical presentation of this disease.

question:
I am a 62-year-old man who recently found myself in the emergency department due to severe chest pain. For the past several days, I had been feeling unwell, experiencing lower back pain, chest pain, discomfort when swallowing, a persistent cough, and what I believed to be a fever. A few weeks prior, I had dental pain, which I had been managing by drinking alcohol.

Upon my arrival at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 104°F, my blood pressure was 114/64 mmHg, my pulse was at 120 beats per minute, and my respirations were 22 per minute. My oxygen saturation level was 92% on room air. During the examination, the doctor noted erythema in my submandibular area and detected a coarse, rasping sound when listening to my heart.

I underwent a CT scan of my chest and an ECG to further investigate my symptoms. The medical team also took some blood tests to assess my condition. While I do not have specific lab results to share, I was informed that my health situation required careful attention and further evaluation.
options: A. Esophageal rupture B. Ludwig angina C. Mediastinitis D. Myocardial infarction E. Pulmonary embolism
default: Based on your symptoms and the findings from your examination, it appears you may be experiencing a serious condition, possibly related to an infection or inflammation in the chest area, such as pneumonia or an abscess, especially given the history of dental pain and the erythema in the submandibular area. The elevated temperature, tachycardia, and respiratory distress also suggest a systemic infection or sepsis. The coarse, rasping sound during the heart examination could indicate pericarditis or another cardiac issue. Immediate medical attention and further evaluation, including the results of your CT scan and blood tests, are crucial for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment. Please follow up closely with your healthcare team for the best course of action.

question:
I am a 7-year-old girl who recently visited the emergency department with my mother due to swelling around my left eye. It all started yesterday morning when I woke up and noticed a painful, warm lump on my left eyelid. The lump felt soft to the touch, and although it was uncomfortable, moving my eye did not make the pain worse. 

During the examination, the doctor observed that my upper left eyelid was red and swollen, and it looked like the hair follicles in that area were affected. When the doctor gently pressed on the swollen area, some pus drained from it. The doctor mentioned they would consider what might be causing these symptoms.
options: A. Hordeolum B. Dacryocystitis C. Blepharitis D. Xanthelasma E. Chalazion
default: It sounds like you might have a stye, which is an infection of the oil glands in your eyelid. The swelling, redness, and pus are common signs. It's important to keep the area clean and follow any care instructions your doctor gives you. If it doesn't improve or gets worse, you should see the doctor again.

question: I am a 17-year-old African-American male, and I visited my family physician recently because I noticed red-tinged urine about a week ago. This change occurred while I was dealing with a cold. I mentioned to my doctor that I had experienced this issue before. My father accompanied me to the appointment, and he noted that he has had similar occurrences at times as well. During the visit, we discussed my symptoms and the history of this condition in our family.
options: A. Acute cystitis B. Acute interstitial nephritis C. Sickle cell trait D. Acute glomerulonephritis E. Hemophilia
default: It sounds like you may be experiencing a condition known as hematuria, which is the presence of blood in urine. Given your family history and the recurrence of this issue, it could be related to a hereditary condition, such as benign familial hematuria or another underlying issue. It's important to follow up with your physician for further evaluation, which may include urine tests or imaging studies, to determine the exact cause and ensure appropriate management.

question:
I recently visited the doctor because I had been experiencing extreme fatigue for the past two days. Additionally, I noticed that my skin appeared yellow, which concerned me. I didn’t have any other symptoms, as I did not experience fever or headache. I mentioned to the doctor that I had used illicit intravenous drugs in the past. 

I moved from Africa to the United States when I was 18, and I realized I did not have any immunization records. During the visit, my vital signs were taken: my heart rate was 72 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 14 breaths per minute, my temperature was 37.9°C (100.2°F), and my blood pressure was 100/74 mm Hg. The physical examination was mostly unremarkable, except for some mild diffuse tenderness in my abdomen.

The doctor ordered routine blood tests, which revealed significantly elevated alanine aminotransferase levels. Additionally, a hepatitis viral panel was conducted. The results indicated that I was positive for HBsAg and IgM anti-HBc, while the other tests for hepatitis A, C, and D were negative. Based on these findings, the doctor discussed the likely diagnosis with me.
options: A. Past hepatitis B infection B. Chronic hepatitis B C. Acute hepatitis A D. Acute hepatitis D superinfection E. Acute hepatitis B
default: Based on your symptoms of extreme fatigue, jaundice (yellowing of the skin), elevated alanine aminotransferase levels, and the positive results for HBsAg and IgM anti-HBc, the likely diagnosis is acute hepatitis B infection. The presence of IgM anti-HBc indicates a recent infection, and the elevated liver enzymes suggest liver inflammation. It's important to follow up with your doctor for further management and monitoring.

question:
I am a 62-year-old man who was recently brought to the emergency department after experiencing syncope. It all started suddenly while I was carrying my groceries to the car; I felt palpitations and then lost consciousness. I don’t remember anything else from that moment. I did not experience any chest pain or dizziness prior to the event. 

My medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, gastroparesis, and osteoarthritis of the knees. I take several medications, including lisinopril, metformin, and ondansetron as needed for nausea. Additionally, I take methadone daily for chronic pain. 

Upon examination, I had an abrasion on my forehead, but otherwise, I appeared well. My temperature was measured at 37.2 °C (98.9 F), my heart rate was 104 beats per minute and regular, and my blood pressure was 135/70 mm Hg. While I was in the emergency department, I lost consciousness again. The telemetry monitoring showed I was experiencing polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with cyclic changes in the QRS axis, which resolved on its own after about 30 seconds. 

Blood tests, including a complete blood count, serum electrolytes, and thyroid studies, came back normal, as did my cardiac enzymes. I am now seeking to understand the likely underlying cause of my syncope.
options:
A. Prolonged QT interval B. Acute myocardial ischemia C. Shortened PR interval D. Fast accessory conduction pathway E. Prinzmetal angina F. Brugada syndrome G. Hypomagnesemia
"
default:
The syncope you experienced, particularly in the context of polymorphic ventricular tachycardia (VT) observed on telemetry, suggests a likely underlying cause of a cardiac arrhythmia. Given your history of hypertension and diabetes, as well as the use of methadone, which can prolong the QT interval, it is plausible that you may have developed a drug-induced long QT syndrome leading to the polymorphic VT (often seen in Torsades de Pointes). 

Additionally, electrolyte imbalances, particularly hypokalemia or hypomagnesemia, can also contribute to such arrhythmias, although your initial blood tests were normal. The combination of your medications, especially methadone, and potential electrolyte disturbances could be the underlying cause of your syn

question:
I am a 60-year-old female who recently went to the emergency department due to severe pain and vision loss in my left eye. The symptoms began suddenly while I was driving through a dark tunnel, which was an unusual experience for me. I had never encountered anything like this before and did not have any prior issues with my eyes. 

When I arrived at the emergency department, the medical staff assessed my left eye, which was poorly responsive to light and felt hard to the touch. The pain was intense and concerning, and I was anxious about the sudden changes in my vision. The situation was alarming, as I had no previous history of ophthalmologic problems. I hoped to find out what was causing these troubling symptoms and to receive the appropriate care.
options: A. Open angle glaucoma B. Closed angle glaucoma C. Cataract D. Central retinal artery occlusion E. Central retinal vein occlusion
default: Based on your symptoms—sudden severe pain, vision loss, a hard feeling in the eye, and poor responsiveness to light—it's possible you may be experiencing acute glaucoma, particularly angle-closure glaucoma. This condition can cause a rapid increase in intraocular pressure, leading to pain and vision changes. It's crucial to seek immediate ophthalmologic evaluation and treatment, as this condition can lead to permanent vision loss if not addressed promptly. Please follow up with an eye specialist for a comprehensive examination and appropriate management.

question:
I am a 35-year-old woman who recently experienced an upper respiratory infection. I went to the emergency department due to a concerning set of symptoms. Initially, I felt a burning sensation in my toes, which was accompanied by numbness. Over the past few days, I noticed increasing weakness in my lower limbs, and this weakness began to extend to my arms and face. At this point, I find it difficult to get up from a chair without assistance.

When I arrived at the emergency department, my temperature was recorded at 37.0°C (98.6°F). My blood pressure was 145/89 mm Hg, my heart rate was 99 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate was 12 breaths per minute. My oxygen saturation was at 95% while breathing room air. During the physical examination, the doctor noted diminished breath sounds in both lung fields and observed that my inspiratory effort was noticeably poor. Additionally, when my lower abdomen was palpated, they found a palpable bladder. In terms of strength, I was assessed to be 3 out of 5 in my lower extremities bilaterally, although my sensation remained intact.
options: A. Acute disseminated encephalomyelitis B. Adrenoleukodystrophy C. Guillain-Barré syndrome D. Multiple sclerosis E. Myasthenia Gravis
default: Your symptoms and clinical findings suggest a possible case of Guillain-Barré syndrome (GBS), particularly given the recent upper respiratory infection and the progressive weakness in your limbs. The burning sensation in your toes, numbness, and the weakness extending to your arms and face are characteristic of this condition. The diminished breath sounds and poor inspiratory effort indicate potential respiratory involvement, which can occur in GBS. The palpable bladder suggests possible autonomic dysfunction, which can also be associated with GBS. Immediate medical evaluation and monitoring are crucial, as GBS can lead to respiratory failure and requires prompt treatment.

question:
I am an 82-year-old woman who recently sought treatment in the emergency department due to severe pain in my right flank and a fever that had persisted for the past two days. I was also experiencing difficulties with urination. My medical history has been generally unremarkable.

Upon my arrival, the medical team conducted a urinalysis, which indicated the presence of leukocytes and gram-negative bacilli. To further investigate the cause of my symptoms, I underwent a contrast computed tomography scan of my abdomen. The results revealed a large mass in the retroperitoneal area that was compressing my right ureter, leading to hydronephrosis in my right kidney.

Following this diagnosis, the medical team excised the mass. They then performed a histopathologic evaluation to determine its nature. The findings indicated that the mass was malignant. I am now awaiting further information about the diagnosis and the next steps in my treatment plan.
options: A. Liposarcoma B. Lipoma C. Rhabdomyosarcoma D. Teratoma E. Leiomyosarcoma
default:
Based on your symptoms and the findings from the imaging and histopathology, it appears that you have a malignant retroperitoneal mass causing ureteral obstruction and hydronephrosis. The presence of leukocytes and gram-negative bacilli in your urinalysis suggests a urinary tract infection, likely secondary to the obstruction.

The next steps in your treatment plan will likely involve a multidisciplinary approach, including:

1. **Oncology Consultation**: To discuss the type of malignancy, staging, and treatment options, which may include surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation therapy.

2. **Urology Follow-Up**: To address the hydronephrosis and ensure proper kidney function, possibly involving the placement of a stent or nephrostomy if needed

question:
I am a 22-year-old male who arrived at the emergency department after being involved in a motor vehicle accident. I was conscious and able to communicate with the hospital staff, although I was in significant pain and had various bruises and scrapes on my body. I had been driving when a head-on collision occurred.

Upon evaluation, my temperature was recorded at 99.5°F, with a pulse rate of 112 beats per minute and a blood pressure of 120/70 mmHg. My breathing rate was 18 breaths per minute, and my oxygen saturation was 99% while on room air. The medical team performed a full trauma assessment, during which they noted that I had no strength (0/5) in my right upper extremity, particularly in extending my wrist.

I was started on IV fluids and given morphine for pain relief. Radiography was ordered to further evaluate my condition. During the assessment, the medical team noted bilateral breath sounds, a normal heart rhythm, and no signs of jugular venous distension. Approximately 30 minutes later, my blood pressure was measured again and recorded at 122/70 mmHg.
options: A. Humeral neck B. Midshaft humerus C. Supracondylar D. Ulnar E. Radial
default: Based on the information provided, you are likely experiencing a significant injury to your right upper extremity, possibly indicating a radial nerve injury or a cervical spine injury, given the complete loss of strength in wrist extension. The vital signs show mild tachycardia but stable blood pressure, and your oxygen saturation is normal, suggesting no immediate respiratory distress. The bruises and scrapes indicate trauma, but the absence of jugular venous distension and normal heart rhythm are reassuring. The medical team will likely focus on imaging to assess for fractures or other injuries, particularly in the cervical spine and the right arm. Continuous monitoring and further evaluation will be essential to determine the extent of your injuries and guide treatment.

question:
I am a 4-year-old girl who was taken to the emergency department after experiencing persistent vomiting and abdominal pain. My parents discovered that I was unwell when they returned home to find me in this state while I had been under the care of a babysitter. I have been healthy overall, but my family has a history of various medical issues, including depression, diabetes, and cancer.

Upon arrival at the hospital, I was minimally responsive and confused. My temperature was recorded at 100°F, and my vital signs showed a pulse of 140 beats per minute and respirations at 22 breaths per minute. I was vomiting, and the contents were bloody. The medical staff conducted a physical examination and ordered laboratory studies to investigate my condition.

During the examination, the doctors noted that there were a few radiopaque objects visible in my stomach through radiography. I was undergoing further testing, including urine and serum toxicology, to determine the cause of my symptoms and any possible intoxication.
options: A. Acetaminophen B. Aspirin C. Iron D. Lead E. Nortriptyline
default: Given the symptoms of persistent vomiting, abdominal pain, confusion, and the presence of radiopaque objects in the stomach, there is a strong suspicion of foreign body ingestion, possibly involving items like batteries or coins. The bloody vomit raises concern for potential internal injury or bleeding. The medical team will likely focus on stabilizing your condition, addressing any immediate threats, and determining the nature of the ingested objects through imaging and toxicology tests. Prompt intervention is crucial to prevent complications.

question:
I am a 45-year-old African-American woman who recently experienced some troubling symptoms. I noticed I had difficulty breathing, along with a persistent cough and chest pain that was non-radiating. The pain seemed to ease when I leaned forward, but it intensified when I leaned backward. During a medical examination, the doctor listened to my chest and noted a scratchy rub that was most prominent when I was leaning forward. 

The examination did not indicate any signs of Kussmaul's sign, pulsus paradoxus, or a pericardial knock, which are all terms I learned during the visit. Although I was unsure about what was happening, the doctor explained that my symptoms pointed towards a specific condition. I left the appointment with a better understanding of my situation and felt reassured that we were working toward a diagnosis.
options: A. Cardiac tamponade B. Constrictive pericarditis C. Acute pericarditis D. Libman-Sacks endocarditis E. Acute myocardial infarction
default: Based on your symptoms—difficulty breathing, persistent cough, chest pain that eases when leaning forward, and the presence of a scratchy rub—it's likely that you are experiencing pericarditis. This condition involves inflammation of the pericardium, the membrane surrounding the heart, and can cause the symptoms you've described. The positional nature of your chest pain and the rub noted during the examination further support this diagnosis. It's important to follow up with your healthcare provider for appropriate management and treatment.

question:
I am a 65-year-old woman who recently visited the clinic for a routine checkup. During this visit, I mentioned that I had unintentionally lost 4.5 kg (9.9 lb) over the past month, although I did not report any other health complaints. 

The healthcare provider measured my vital signs: my pulse rate was 90 beats per minute, my respiratory rate was 18 breaths per minute, my temperature was 37.0°C (98.6°F), and my blood pressure was 150/70 mm Hg. During the examination, they noted an irregularly irregular rhythm in my heart. 

Upon further examination of my neck, the provider observed that my thyroid was markedly enlarged, but there were no signs of lymphadenopathy or bruit. 

Based on these findings, the provider discussed the possibility of a thyroid condition, though specific laboratory tests, including thyroid-stimulating hormone levels and T4 levels, as well as imaging studies, would be needed for a definitive diagnosis. While I was not aware of the specific tests results or their implications at the time, I understood that my symptoms and examination findings were concerning enough to warrant further investigation.
options: A. Graves’ disease B. Hashimoto’s thyroiditis C. Subacute granulomatous thyroiditis D. Toxic adenoma E. Toxic multinodular goiter
default: Based on your symptoms and examination findings, it is likely that you may have a thyroid condition, such as hyperthyroidism or a thyroid nodule, given the enlarged thyroid and unintentional weight loss. The irregular heart rhythm could also be related to thyroid dysfunction. It’s important to follow up with the recommended laboratory tests and imaging studies to determine the exact nature of your thyroid issue and to guide appropriate treatment.

question:
I am a 64-year-old male who recently visited my primary care physician due to pain in my left knee. The pain began suddenly last evening, and I also noticed redness in the skin around the joint. I did not experience any injury or engage in activities that might have caused this discomfort.

Two months prior, I had a similar episode with my right knee, but I chose not to seek medical treatment at that time. That pain resolved after about five days. During my recent examination, the doctor found that my left knee was warm to the touch, erythematous, and extremely tender when pressed. I experienced limited range of motion in both flexion and extension due to pain, and there was a noticeable crepitus with passive movement of the joint. 

My vital signs were within normal limits, and I was not running a fever. The doctor recommended aspiration of the left knee joint, which was scheduled for further evaluation.
options: A. Decreased serum calcium levels and elevated phosphate levels B. Autoimmune destruction of pancreatic islet cells and elevated blood glucose levels C. Insulin insensitivity and elevated blood glucose levels D. Bronzing of the skin and elevated blood glucose levels E. Kayser-Fleischer rings and decreased serum ceruloplasmin
solution_text: Bronzing of the skin and elevated blood glucose levels
default: Based on your symptoms—sudden onset of pain, redness, warmth, tenderness, limited range of motion, and a history of a similar episode—it's possible you are experiencing an acute inflammatory condition, such as gout or pseudogout, or potentially septic arthritis. The aspiration of the knee joint will help determine the cause by analyzing the synovial fluid for crystals, infection, or other abnormalities. It's important to follow up on the results for appropriate treatment.
alternative: Bronzing of the skin and elevated blood glucose levels

question:
I am a 78-year-old man who began experiencing fatigue and shortness of breath during physical activities about four weeks ago. These symptoms gradually developed and have not improved since their onset. I have no previous history of anemia or nutritional deficiencies. 

Six months ago, I had a significant medical event—a ST-elevation myocardial infarction—after which I underwent coronary artery bypass graft surgery. This was complicated by recurrent episodes of unstable ventricular tachycardia. Currently, I take several medications, including rosuvastatin, aspirin, and amiodarone.

At my recent check-up, my blood pressure was measured at 100/70 mm Hg, my pulse was 71 beats per minute, and my temperature was 36.5°C (97.7°F). During the physical examination, I appeared lethargic and tired. My skin was noted to be dry and coarse, and there was noticeable generalized pitting edema.

Further evaluations indicated the presence of normochromic, normocytic anemia, along with decreased serum iron levels, decreased total iron-binding capacity, and increased serum ferritin levels. I am currently awaiting further assessment to determine the most likely cause of my anemia.
options: A. Iron deficiency anemia B. Hemolytic anemia C. Anemia of chronic disease D. Pernicious anemia E. Thalassemia
default: Given your symptoms and recent medical history, the most likely cause of your normochromic, normocytic anemia with decreased serum iron levels, decreased total iron-binding capacity, and increased serum ferritin is anemia of chronic disease (ACD). This condition is often associated with chronic inflammation or underlying health issues, such as your recent myocardial infarction and heart surgery. The presence of generalized pitting edema and dry skin may also suggest fluid retention or heart failure, which can further contribute to your symptoms and anemia. It would be important to continue evaluating your cardiac function and any potential inflammatory processes that could be affecting your blood counts.

question:
I am a 45-year-old female who recently went to the emergency department because I was experiencing gross hematuria and acute, colicky flank pain. I had never had any prior episodes of hematuria. Over the past several weeks, I had been taking high doses of acetaminophen and aspirin to manage persistent upper back pain. 

When I arrived at the emergency department, my blood pressure and temperature were within normal limits. However, during the examination, the doctors found that I had proteinuria. They conducted a physical examination, which did not reveal any palpable flank masses. 

At this point, I was uncertain about what was causing my symptoms, but I hoped to find answers and relief from the pain I was experiencing.
options: A. Diffuse cortical necrosis B. Chronic pyelonephritis C. Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease D. Papillary necrosis E. Acute Nephrolithiasis
default: Your symptoms of gross hematuria, acute colicky flank pain, and proteinuria, combined with your recent high-dose use of acetaminophen and aspirin, suggest a possible diagnosis of acute kidney injury or nephropathy, potentially due to analgesic nephropathy. This condition can occur with prolonged use of analgesics, leading to kidney damage and associated symptoms. It would be important to conduct further imaging studies, such as a CT scan, to evaluate for any urinary tract obstruction, stones, or other renal pathology. Additionally, monitoring kidney function and considering a referral to a nephrologist may be warranted for further evaluation and management.

question:
I was admitted to the hospital four days after undergoing coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG) due to a myocardial infarction (MI). I am 68 years old and have a history of insulin-controlled diabetes, hypertension, and hyperlipidemia. 

Initially, after the surgery, I experienced a resolution of my chest pain, which was a relief. However, I began to have chest pain again that felt different from what I had before. I noticed that the pain worsened when I took deep breaths but seemed to lessen when I leaned forward. In contrast, lying flat made the pain more uncomfortable.

During my examination, the medical team checked my vital signs, which were within normal limits. They also listened to my heart and found no murmurs. I was informed that my CK-mB levels came back normal, and a repeat electrocardiogram (ECG) was performed, the results of which were reviewed by the doctors.

I am awaiting further assessment to determine the cause of this new chest pain and what steps will be taken next in my treatment plan.
options: A. Ventricular aneurysm B. Ventricular septal rupture C. Papillary muscle rupture D. Acute pericarditis E. Dressler's syndrome
default:
Based on your symptoms and history, the new chest pain you're experiencing is likely due to post-operative pericarditis, which is inflammation of the pericardium that can occur after cardiac surgery. The pain worsening with deep breaths and improving when leaning forward is characteristic of this condition. 

Given that your CK-MB levels are normal and there are no murmurs on auscultation, it seems less likely that your pain is due to myocardial ischemia or other cardiac complications. The medical team will likely consider imaging studies, such as an echocardiogram, to assess for pericardial effusion or other abnormalities. Treatment may include anti-inflammatory medications. It's important to follow up closely with your healthcare team for further evaluation and management.

question:
I am a 35-year-old lawyer. Recently, I experienced a sudden onset of vision loss, which prompted my coworkers to bring me to the emergency department. This incident followed a challenging week in which I lost three cases. The day before my vision loss, I noticed weakness and paralysis in my left wrist, which was concerning to me.

In the emergency department, I underwent a physical examination. The doctors noted that my reflexes were somewhat diminished, rated at 2 out of 4, but my muscular strength in all extremities was normal, rated at 5 out of 5. During the evaluation, I felt indifferent to my situation and exhibited a flat affect. Fortunately, I did not experience slurring of my words.

To further investigate my condition, the medical team conducted a CT scan without contrast and an MRI of my brain. Both imaging results appeared unremarkable, leaving the doctors to consider potential diagnoses. At this point, I remain focused on understanding the cause of my symptoms and what steps may be necessary for my recovery.
options: A. Factitious disorder B. Transient ischemic attack C. Somatization disorder D. Major depressive disorder E. Conversion disorder
default: Your symptoms, including sudden vision loss, left wrist weakness, diminished reflexes, and flat affect, suggest a possible neurological issue. Given the unremarkable CT and MRI results, conditions like a transient ischemic attack (TIA) or a functional neurological disorder could be considered. The emotional stress from losing cases may also contribute to your symptoms. It's essential to follow up with a neurologist for further evaluation, which may include additional tests or assessments to determine the underlying cause and appropriate treatment.

question:
I am a 53-year-old woman who recently experienced a sudden onset of respiratory distress that lasted for several hours. I have a medical history that includes a myocardial infarction two years ago. When I visited my physician, my vital signs were recorded: my blood pressure was 70/40 mm Hg, my pulse was 92 beats per minute, and my respiratory rate was 28 breaths per minute. My oxygen saturation level was 92% while breathing room air.

During the physical examination, the doctor noted bilateral basal crepitations when listening to my lungs. An echocardiogram was performed, which showed that my ejection fraction was 34%. Following this evaluation, I was admitted to the medical floor and started on furosemide. Over the next 24 hours, I produced 400 mL of urine. 

Subsequent tests indicated that my blood urea nitrogen level was 45 mg/dL, and my serum creatinine level was 1.85 mg/dL. The fractional excretion of sodium was measured at 0.89%, and a urinalysis revealed muddy brown granular casts. I am now awaiting further evaluation of these findings and their implications for my condition.
options: A. Acute glomerulonephritis B. Chronic kidney disease C. Acute pyelonephritis D. Acute interstitial nephritis E. Acute tubular necrosis
default:
Based on your symptoms and test results, it appears you are experiencing acute kidney injury (AKI) likely due to acute tubular necrosis (ATN), possibly secondary to volume depletion or decreased renal perfusion related to your hypotension (70/40 mm Hg) and heart failure (ejection fraction of 34%). The presence of muddy brown granular casts in your urinalysis supports this diagnosis, as they are indicative of tubular damage.

Your elevated blood urea nitrogen (BUN) and creatinine levels further confirm renal impairment. The low fractional excretion of sodium (FENa of 0.89%) suggests that your kidneys are attempting to conserve sodium, which is typical in prerenal causes of AKI, but the presence of

question:
I am a 56-year-old man who recently visited my physician due to a worsening pain in my left buttock that has persisted for two months. The pain is a deep, dull ache, and I’ve noticed it intensifies at night. I haven't experienced any recent trauma that could explain the discomfort. 

I have a history of hyperlipidemia and have been a smoker for the past 30 years, consuming about one pack of cigarettes daily. I also drink one beer each night, but I do not use illicit drugs. My only medication is simvastatin. 

During my physical examination, the doctor noted tenderness in the left gluteal region, but the neurological assessment did not reveal any focal findings. An x-ray of my pelvis showed a 4-cm, poorly defined, osteolytic lesion in the left ilium, characterized by a moth-eaten pattern of bone destruction and multiple well-defined sclerotic lesions, along with an aggressive periosteal reaction. The rest of the physical examination, including a rectal exam, showed no abnormalities. Additionally, a chest x-ray and abdominal ultrasonography did not show any issues. Based on these findings, the physician is considering a likely diagnosis.
options: A. Osteosarcoma B. Giant cell tumor C. Fibrosarcoma D. Plasmacytoma E. Ewing sarcoma F. Osteochondroma G. Chondrosarcoma
default: Given the details provided, including the osteolytic lesion in the left ilium with a moth-eaten pattern and aggressive periosteal reaction, the likely diagnosis is a primary bone malignancy, such as osteosarcoma or possibly a metastatic lesion, especially considering your history of smoking and hyperlipidemia. The characteristics of the lesion raise concern for malignancy, and further evaluation, including a biopsy, would be necessary to confirm the diagnosis.

question:
I am 21 years old and recently my roommate brought me to the emergency department because she was concerned about my behavior over the past 10 days. She noticed I had been acting strangely, moving and talking on the phone at all hours of the night. I was only sleeping about one to two hours each night, and I spent hours pacing up and down our apartment, often talking about my plans to "save the world." 

I was speaking very quickly, and when my roommate asked if I felt anything was wrong, I denied it. I mentioned that I had made great progress on my plans. I recalled experiencing similar feelings about two years ago, which led to a hospitalization for about two weeks. 

Although I have never been diagnosed with depression, I did have a period last year where I struggled with low energy and motivation, making it difficult for me to attend class or see friends. I do not hear voices or see visual hallucinations. My roommate's concern prompted this visit, and I am now evaluating my current state and its implications.
options: A. Schizoaffective disorder B. Major depressive disorder C. Bipolar I disorder D. Bipolar II disorder E. Dysthymic disorder
default: Based on your description, it sounds like you may be experiencing a manic episode, which is often associated with bipolar disorder. The symptoms you've mentioned—reduced sleep, increased energy, racing thoughts, and grandiose plans—are characteristic of mania. Your previous hospitalization and the low energy period suggest a possible pattern of mood fluctuations. It's important to discuss these symptoms with a mental health professional for a thorough evaluation and appropriate treatment.

question:
I am a 40-year-old male who was involved in a motorcycle accident and subsequently presented to the emergency room. Upon my arrival, I experienced a significant drop in blood pressure, measured at 70/50 mmHg, and my heart rate was elevated at 130 bpm. During my hospitalization, I developed oliguria, which is a condition characterized by reduced urine output. 

Throughout my stay, medical staff conducted various urine studies to assess my kidney function. After receiving treatment, I was eventually discharged from the hospital with my renal function restored. The medical team identified the underlying issues that contributed to my kidney problems during my recovery.
options: A. Acute pyelonephritis B. Diabetic glomerulopathy C. Rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis D. Acute tubular necrosis E. Membranous glomerulonephritis
default: Based on your description, it appears you experienced acute kidney injury (AKI) likely due to hypovolemic shock from the motorcycle accident, leading to reduced renal perfusion and oliguria. The significant drop in blood pressure and elevated heart rate suggest a state of shock, which can impair kidney function. The medical team likely identified that the AKI was reversible with appropriate treatment, such as fluid resuscitation and stabilization of blood pressure, which restored your renal function before discharge.

question:
I am a 17-year-old girl who visited the emergency department due to severe abdominal pain that had persisted for five days. The pain was cramping in nature, and I also experienced nausea and vomiting. Additionally, I felt discomfort while urinating. I am sexually active with one male partner, and we have not always used condoms consistently. Three days prior to my visit, I experienced a burning sensation during intercourse.

My menstrual cycle is regular, occurring every 28 days and lasting for five days. My last period started three weeks ago. During the examination, my temperature was recorded at 38.5°C (101.3°F), my pulse was 83 beats per minute, and my blood pressure was 110/70 mm Hg. The physical examination revealed tenderness in my lower abdominal quadrants. A pelvic examination indicated cervical motion tenderness and a purulent discharge from the cervix.

These symptoms prompted the medical staff to consider potential diagnoses, given the combination of abdominal pain, urinary discomfort, and other findings.
options: A. Pyelonephritis B. Ectopic pregnancy C. Ovarian cyst rupture D. Appendicitis E. Vulvovaginitis F. Cystitis G. Pelvic inflammatory disease
default: Based on the symptoms and findings you've described, the most likely diagnosis is pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), possibly due to a sexually transmitted infection (STI) such as chlamydia or gonorrhea. The combination of severe abdominal pain, cervical motion tenderness, purulent discharge, fever, and urinary discomfort strongly suggests an infection of the reproductive organs. It's important to follow up with appropriate testing and treatment, as PID can lead to serious complications if not addressed promptly.

question:
I am a 65-year-old man who was brought to the emergency department after experiencing distressing symptoms at my nursing home. I coughed up large amounts of blood-tinged sputum, which prompted immediate medical attention. Recently, I had been treated for an upper respiratory tract infection with antibiotics. My history includes a long-standing productive cough that has worsened since I had a stroke three years ago. 

Before my stroke, I was a daily smoker, consuming a pack of cigarettes for 40 years. I quit smoking after the stroke. Upon arrival at the emergency department, I felt short of breath and appeared visibly distressed. My vital signs indicated a temperature of 38°C (100.4°F), a pulse rate of 92 beats per minute, and a blood pressure reading of 145/85 mm Hg. A pulse oximetry test showed my oxygen saturation was at 92% while breathing room air. 

During the physical examination, the doctor noted digital clubbing and cyanosis of my lips. I was also found to have coarse crackles in my chest upon auscultation. An x-ray of my chest was performed, revealing increased translucency and tram-track opacities in the right lower lung field.
options:
A. Bronchiectasis B. Chronic bronchitis C. Aspiration pneumonia D. Emphysema E. Pulmonary embolism F. Lung cancer
"
default:
Based on the provided information, the patient is likely experiencing a significant respiratory issue, possibly related to chronic lung disease, given his history of long-term smoking, productive cough, and recent upper respiratory infection. The presence of blood-tinged sputum, digital clubbing, and cyanosis suggests a serious underlying condition, such as bronchiectasis or lung cancer, particularly considering the x-ray findings of increased translucency and tram-track opacities, which are indicative of bronchial wall thickening.

The combination of symptoms—coughing up blood, shortness of breath, fever, and crackles on auscultation—points towards a possible infectious process or exacerbation of chronic lung disease. Given his history of smoking and the acute presentation, further

question:
I am a 6-year-old boy who was taken to the physician because I had a headache, cough, runny nose, and a low-grade fever. These symptoms started when I woke up that morning. Until then, I had been healthy, except for a urinary tract infection that I had a week ago, which was treated with trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole and has since resolved. 

Both my parents have a history of allergic rhinitis, which might be relevant. When I arrived at the doctor’s office, my temperature was measured at 37.8°C (100°F). During the physical examination, the doctor noted that I had a runny nose and tenderness around my forehead and cheeks, indicating possible sinus involvement. Additionally, I had swollen lymph nodes in my neck. 

The doctor performed some laboratory studies, but I am not aware of the results. My symptoms and the findings led to a discussion about what could be causing my condition. The physician considered various possibilities based on my symptoms and medical history.
options: A. Primary autoimmune neutropenia B. Folate deficiency C. Medication side effect D. Acute lymphocytic leukemia E. CMV infection F. EBV infection G. Acute myelogenous leukemia
default: Based on your symptoms of headache, cough, runny nose, low-grade fever, tenderness around the forehead and cheeks, and swollen lymph nodes, it is likely that you have acute viral rhinosinusitis, commonly known as a viral sinus infection. Your recent history of a urinary tract infection and your parents' history of allergic rhinitis may also suggest a predisposition to respiratory issues. The acute onset of symptoms and the physical findings support this diagnosis. If the physician performed laboratory studies, they may have been to rule out bacterial sinusitis or other infections, but the overall presentation is consistent with a viral cause.

question:
I am a 45-year-old woman who recently visited the emergency department due to a painful mass on the right side of my neck. This mass has been present for about a week and has gradually increased in size, becoming more painful when I touch it. Along with the mass, I have experienced night sweats, unintentional weight loss, and episodes of diarrhea. 

A few weeks prior, I had a minor cold, but since then, I haven’t noticed any other significant symptoms. During my visit, the medical staff recorded my temperature, which was 100°F, and my blood pressure was measured at 122/80 mmHg. My pulse was notably elevated at 160 beats per minute, while my respirations were 19 per minute, and my oxygen saturation was stable at 100% on room air.

During the physical examination, the healthcare provider noted that my thyroid was diffusely enlarged and tender to the touch. An ECG was performed as part of the assessment. I am awaiting further evaluation to determine the most likely cause of these symptoms and the appropriate diagnosis.
options: A. Graves disease B. Hashimoto thyroiditis C. Riedel thyroiditis D. Silent thyroiditis E. Subacute granulomatous thyroiditis
default: Based on your symptoms—painful neck mass, night sweats, unintentional weight loss, diarrhea, fever, tachycardia, and a diffusely enlarged and tender thyroid—there is a concern for thyroiditis, possibly subacute thyroiditis (de Quervain's thyroiditis) or a more serious condition like thyroid cancer or an autoimmune process such as Graves' disease. The combination of systemic symptoms (night sweats, weight loss) and the thyroid findings suggests a need for further evaluation, including thyroid function tests, imaging, and possibly a biopsy to rule out malignancy. Immediate attention to the tachycardia and any potential hyperthyroid symptoms is also warranted.

question:
I am 23 years old and have one child. Recently, I went to the emergency department due to severe lower abdominal pain that began several hours earlier. Over the past two days, I had been experiencing fever, malaise, and nausea. My last menstrual period was three weeks ago, and my medical history is otherwise unremarkable. 

In the past month, I had three sexual partners and have been using oral contraception. Upon arrival at the hospital, my temperature was recorded at 38.8°C (101.8°F), and my blood pressure was 120/75 mm Hg. During the physical examination, the doctor noted tenderness in my lower abdominal quadrants, as well as uterine and adnexal tenderness. 

A urine test showed that I was not pregnant. During a speculum examination, the doctor observed inflammation of the cervix, along with motion tenderness and a yellow-white purulent discharge. Based on these findings, I understand that there is a concern for a specific diagnosis related to my symptoms.
options: A. Vaginitis B. Cervicitis C. Pelvic inflammatory disease D. Ruptured ectopic pregnancy E. Urinary tract infection
default: Based on your symptoms and examination findings, you are likely experiencing pelvic inflammatory disease (PID). The key indicators include your fever, lower abdominal pain, cervical inflammation, and purulent discharge, along with a history of multiple sexual partners. PID is often associated with sexually transmitted infections, such as chlamydia or gonorrhea. It's important to receive appropriate treatment to prevent complications.

question:
I am a 21-year-old woman who recently visited the emergency room due to pain in my right arm and limited range of motion. I couldn't recall any specific trauma to the arm that might have caused the pain. Alongside this discomfort, I experienced diarrhea and nausea. 

In addition to these symptoms, I have been sexually active with one male partner and noticed that I experience pain during intercourse. During the examination, the doctor found vague tenderness when palpating my abdomen in all four quadrants, but there was no redness or swelling in my right arm. 

I also underwent a fecal occult test, which came back negative. It's worth mentioning that I have been to the emergency room seven times in the past year with similar symptoms, which has been a concerning pattern for me.
options: A. Ulcerative colitis B. Illness anxiety disorder C. Somatization disorder D. Somatoform pain disorder E. Conversion disorder
